commit_message:
Ability to create multiple volumes from api

Added new parameter num_volumes to be provided
for creating multiple volume requests. The display_name
will be used as parameter for indexing the volume names
If the display_name is not provided the name will be
generated based on current timestamp.

Change-Id: Ie269f3b320878938d29d108b53dd30ce127f75fd
Implements: bp/create-multiple-volume-from-cli

The nova api for server show only returns the flavor id as of now. To get the name of the flavor, we have to do a flavor show api call. Also, with this patch, you only get the flavor name in server details when the flavor is deleted and nova server show api decides to return the entire flavor details from the system_metadata. If the flavor is not deleted and we do a server show, we have to do the flavor show call since we only get the flavor id in that request.

Also the nova reviewers dont want to change this for the nova v2 api, and only the v3 api will be changed. So i am pushing a new patchset for these changes.'}, {'account_id': 6124, 'date': '2013-12-18 12:25:05.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-18 13:14:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

commit_message:
Use flavor details from server data if available

* Nova patch (https://review.openstack.org/59860) will disable showing
  deleted flavors
* Hence use deleted flavor details from server data instead of querying
  flavor api
* Nova patch will not show deleted flavors because flavor id's are not
  unique and any duplicate deleted/non-deleted flavor with same flavor
  id can be returned

Closes-Bug: #1153926
Change-Id: I74f6e969aea1e1b37c13bc2525a5e3f9f57a6f14

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-22 17:37:30.000000000', 'message': 'Fix handling of application errors in image cache

Prior to this change, when the image cache encountered an Exception when
iterating through an image that was returned by the underlying
application, it would not always distinguish that exception from an
exception with caching. However, it is necessary for caching exceptions
to be logged and ignored, and underlying image iterator exceptions to be
passed through.

This patch catches underlying exceptions at the source and flags them.
Then, in outermost exception handling, any underlying exceptions are simply
re-raised, whereas cache exceptions are logged and ignored and the image
iterator is passed through as needed.

This patch also stops using "GlanceException" to (incorrectly) try to
distinguish between caching and underlying exceptions. A surprising but
beneficial side effect is that the cache no longer attempts to be
responsible for raising Exceptions when it encounters scenarios like an
invalid image size or invalid image checksum--raising those errors is
the responsibility of the underlying application.

Fixes bug 1252277

Change-Id: Ib2ab4066c43adf98ad9b5f9441a3fb8a7206a5c1
'}]
commit_message:
Fix handling of application errors in image cache

Prior to this change, when the image cache encountered an Exception when
iterating through an image that was returned by the underlying
application, it would not always distinguish that exception from an
exception with caching. However, it is necessary for caching exceptions
to be logged and ignored, and underlying image iterator exceptions to be
passed through.

This patch catches underlying exceptions at the source and flags them.
Then, in outermost exception handling, any underlying exceptions are simply
re-raised, whereas cache exceptions are logged and ignored and the image
iterator is passed through as needed.

This patch also stops using "GlanceException" to (incorrectly) try to
distinguish between caching and underlying exceptions. A surprising but
beneficial side effect is that the cache no longer attempts to be
responsible for raising Exceptions when it encounters scenarios like an
invalid image size or invalid image checksum--raising those errors is
the responsibility of the underlying application.

Fixes bug 1252277

Change-Id: Ib2ab4066c43adf98ad9b5f9441a3fb8a7206a5c1

commit_message:
Add redirect action when unauthorized exception occured.

The parameter "redirect" is not working when the exc_type is "UNAUTHORIZED".
This commit will help to redirect the page if the parameter
"redirect" is not None when unauthorized exception occured.

Closes-Bug: #1256215
Change-Id: I89f2036505e98cc13ccfa781b20ed2e560eb96c5

[{'created': '2013-11-27 20:35:41.000000000', 'message': "Enforce permissions in snapshots temporary dir

Live snapshots creates a temporary directory where libvirt driver
creates a new image from the instance's disk using blockRebase.
Currently this directory is created with 777 permissions making this
directory accessible by all the users in the system.

This patch introduces a new decorator that will change temporary the
file-creation mask during for a method. With it we prevent the images
created in the temporary directory from being world readable without
having to worry about race conditions. We also change the temporary
directory permissions so they have the o+x flag set, which is what
libvirt needs to be able to write in it.

Closes-Bug: #1218372
Change-Id: I767ff5247b4452821727e92b668276004fc0f84d

commit_message:
Enforce permissions in snapshots temporary dir

Live snapshots creates a temporary directory where libvirt driver
creates a new image from the instance's disk using blockRebase.
Currently this directory is created with 777 permissions making this
directory accessible by all the users in the system.

This patch changes the tempdir permissions so they have the o+x
flag set, which is what libvirt needs to be able to write in it and

Closes-Bug: #1227027
Change-Id: I767ff5247b4452821727e92b668276004fc0f84d

commit_message:
Add oslo.rootwrap to devstack gate

oslo.rootwrap recently graduated but was not made part of the
devstack-gate. This change is part of a series of changes affecting
devstack-gate, config and devstack which will collectively fix this:

https://review.openstack.org/#/q/status:open+topic:rootwrap-gate,n,z

This should probably be merged once the config and devstack-gate changes
are in, so that it can be self-testing.

Change-Id: I7b1332c8004845a0dd76e27d871370d41d4524ac

Change when exists notification is sent for rescue

The exists notification is now generated only after the rescue
operation completes successfully.

IIRC when I looked at the tempest issue it failed to cleanup properly from a prior test, and what was happening was the transfer still existed so the "expected" count of 1 transfer, delete and 0 transfer is what was broken.

The tempest log I looked at might be different to the one you saw. The one I saw failed in the comparison of the volume-id:

self.assertEqual(volume['id'], body[0]['volume_id'])

A volume delete failed after that because the transfer had not been deleted.

I'm guessing that there were two transfers in the database because the two tempest tests were run simultaneously on different VM's writing to a single db. Resulting in 2 entries in the transfers table.

btw the change to the unit test that I made to exercise this bug exposed the same bug in _transfer_get()"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-20 14:04:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Doesn't seem to work

commit_message:
Fix sqlalchemy bug in transfer_get_all_by_project

Because of incorrect use of the sqlalchemy methods joinedload and filter,
incorrect lists of volume transfers were being returned by
transfer_get_all_by_project().

Change-Id: I378a512611591eec896edd5f217e75f9ff0f8ad3
Closes-Bug: 1262432

commit_message:
Fix work of udp publisher

 * Signature is appended also to udp messages
 * All methods for convert from sample to message are moved to publisher/utils.py
 * In configs metering_secret is moved from group publisher_rpc to publisher
 * Changed tests for udp publisher

Fixes: bug #1259171

Change-Id: Ic7727c69d4be6d17ff00f21e323341efd57122a7

commit_message:
heat_keystoneclient revise get_ec2_keypair

Modify get_ec2_keypair so it's no longer making assumptions about the
number of keypairs a user has, instead we provide create_ec2_keypair,
which just creates and returns a keypair, and get_ec2_keypair just gets
a specified keypair by user and access key ID.

It's now up to the calling resources to manage the lifecycle of the keypairs
(which they should be doing anyway..).  Also make the user_id optional.

Change-Id: I28aa0c2d764b9e957302269598a5910346363d0f
Related-Bug: #1089261
blueprint: instance-users

commit_message:
Store AccessKey secret_key in resource data

Similar to the change for SignalResponder, store the secret key
encrypted in resource data, rather than requesting it from keystone
every time the user requests the SecretKey attribute.

Unlike SignalResponder (which stores the signed URL after using
the keypair to sign the request), we need this to be backwards
compatible, to cope with upgrading heat with stacks in the DB
which contain the AccessKey resource but don't have the secret
stored.

blueprint: instance-users
Related-Bug: #1262177

Change-Id: I92826a6dc028b151d98c0a5e2f6ec27db4b744b9

Have installed ceilometer on Ubuntu 12.04 (LTS) and added the keystone endpoint
with the url (publicurl,internalurl and
adminurl)like:http://192.168.83.7:8777/refer to the "OpenStack
Installation Guide for Ubuntu 12.04 (LTS)". When using  "ceilometer
--debug meter-list",the ceilometerclient log
request url with a double slash after 8777.

Change-Id: I467704b1fe1d38fe0f0e928bd6f6efe3d8925845
Closes-bug: #1262498
'}]
commit_message:
Fix the ceilometerlient log curl request incorrectly

Have installed ceilometer on Ubuntu 12.04 (LTS) and added the keystone endpoint
with the url (publicurl,internalurl and
adminurl)like:http://192.168.83.7:8777/refer to the "OpenStack
Installation Guide for Ubuntu 12.04 (LTS)". When using  "ceilometer
--debug meter-list",the ceilometerclient log
request url with a double slash after 8777.

Change-Id: I467704b1fe1d38fe0f0e928bd6f6efe3d8925845
Closes-bug: #1262498

commit_message:
Add ability to configure Heat and Trove client options

Make the client parameters "ca_file", "cert_file" "insecure" and
"key_file" configurable for Heat client and Trove client.
Partial-Bug: #1263165

commit_message:
Fix charts display in Resource Usage

    Due to an error in a patch, the line 638 of horizon.d3linechart.js
has been commented. The consequence of this is that now charts are not
displayed in the Resource usage panel.

Fixes bug #1266505

Change-Id: Ifc9aa6100efdba6c3efd1ea47638a7934f457913

commit_message:
Remove copyright from empty files

According to policy change in HACKING:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/hacking/#openstack-licensing
empty files should no longer contain copyright notices.

This patch aslo changes files in ironic/openstack/common, which
were changed in oslo https://review.openstack.org/#/c/64082/

Change-Id: I85fdbc2d94200b6e47ad7c9b8717d4578de2eaee
Closes-Bug: #1262424

commit_message:
Added further openstack-config options for RHEL and SUSE platforms

This is a second patch set for migrating the manual copy and paste
configuration file changes to using openstack-config. This completes
the Neutron section for installing on a dedicated controller,
dedicated network node and a compute host.

Change-Id: I5171c7e4573b1e95c41587a81f7c6f803f8975a3

commit_message:
API schema for v3 console_output API

By defining the API schema, it is possible to separate the validation
code from the API method. The API method can be more simple.
In addition, a response of API validation error can be consistent for
the whole Nova API.

Partially implements blueprint nova-api-validation-fw

Change-Id: Ide06b108a669265313c76bd59b3038c24852f6a2

commit_message:
Fix systemctl problem on SLES in ceilometer setup

There is a problem when enable mongodb service on SLES in ceilometer
install section, which uses `systemctl start mongodb.service`.

systemctl is not installed in SLES SP3 by default, and
mongodb.service is not a valid service too. This patch uses common
commands of `service` and `chkconfig` to do the right job.

Change-Id: I3d44f6aba155601030b9b13dc7ef29550e19dc2c
Closes-Bug: #1267297
(cherry picked from commit 928fd5573dfce8d8b435e89f8bc54b9ee4e1b422)

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-06 13:34:23.000000000', 'message': "Non-default option groups in cinder.conf.sample

Script generate_sample.sh generates cinder.conf.sample grouping some options in
[DEFAULT] block when they should be grouped in the specific group, not
default.

E.g.

'topics' option in the cinder/openstack/common/notifier/rpc_notifier2.py
is defined as 'rpc_notifier2' group's member:

notification_topic_opt = cfg.ListOpt(
    'topics', default=['notifications', ],
    help='AMQP topic(s) used for OpenStack notifications')

opt_group = cfg.OptGroup(name='rpc_notifier2',
                         title='Options for rpc_notifier2')

CONF = cfg.CONF
CONF.register_group(opt_group)
CONF.register_opt(notification_topic_opt, opt_group)

but extract_opts.py generates cinder.conf.sample putting the option in
the '[DEFAULT]' block.

bug 1258504

Change-Id: I361097c4349e5f3bcdf5aac1e0142ed83ede30c3

commit_message:
Non-default option groups in cinder.conf.sample

Script generate_sample.sh generates cinder.conf.sample grouping some options in
[DEFAULT] block in spite of the fact that they should be grouped in
the specific group, not default.

E.g.

'topics' option in the cinder/openstack/common/notifier/rpc_notifier2.py
is defined as 'rpc_notifier2' group's member:

notification_topic_opt = cfg.ListOpt(
    'topics', default=['notifications', ],
    help='AMQP topic(s) used for OpenStack notifications')

opt_group = cfg.OptGroup(name='rpc_notifier2',
                         title='Options for rpc_notifier2')

CONF = cfg.CONF
CONF.register_group(opt_group)
CONF.register_opt(notification_topic_opt, opt_group)

but extract_opts.py generates cinder.conf.sample putting the option in
the '[DEFAULT]' block.

Closes-bug: #1258504

Change-Id: I361097c4349e5f3bcdf5aac1e0142ed83ede30c3

configured, it will print nothing when verify with
`ceilometer meter-list`, because the ceilometer-collector catches an
exception of `RuntimeError: No ceilometer.dispatcher extensions found`

This patch add a step for SLES to configure default ceilometer
collector dispatcher to `database`.

commit_message:
Fix ceilometer collector dispatcher on SLES

Follow the guide on SLES SP3 without ceilometer collector dispatcher
configured, it will print nothing when verify with
`ceilometer meter-list`, because the ceilometer-collector catches an
exception of `RuntimeError: No ceilometer.dispatcher extensions found`

This patch add a step for SLES to configure default ceilometer
collector dispatcher to `database`.

Change-Id: Ib2dade0a6f382ec43eac64374e5977df81a48b61
Closes-Bug: #1267318
(cherry picked from commit b129429c8ea78eb0de269666aa53dc62a92c9308)

commit_message:
NFS/GlusterFS: Skip incorrectly formatted shares

Shares should always be of the form address:/volume.  If they are
not (i.e., are missing the '/'), then skip them and issue a warning
message.  This will prevent us from sending incorrect connection_info
dicts to Nova.

Closes-Bug: #1267253

Change-Id: Ic40cd0cdc862b44b0a7d3e5b1d7c4fee8ea1b28d

--allow-insecure options so that pip 1.5 and later will assent to
retrieve the netaddr package even though it's not hosted on PyPI.
The --allow-insecure option is aliased to a clearer
--allow-unverified wording in 1.5, but the old form is being used to
avoid breaking users of 1.4.x and will be valid at least through

Partial-Bug: #1266513

commit_message:
Whitelist external netaddr requirement

* tox.ini(testenv.install_command): Use the --allow-external and
--allow-insecure options so that pip 1.5 and later will assent to
retrieve the netaddr package even though it's not hosted on PyPI.
The --allow-insecure option is aliased to a clearer
--allow-unverified wording in 1.5, but the old form is being used to
avoid breaking users of 1.4.x and will be valid at least through
1.6.x according to comments in the pip source.

Change-Id: I291684fa65279f0cb86f84e0d8e69bfa4b4087c0
Partial-Bug: #1266513

commit_message:
Add API schema for v3 admin_password API

By defining the API schema, it is possible to separate the validation
code from the API method. The API method can be more simple.
In addition, a response of API validation error can be consistent for
the whole Nova API.

Partially implements blueprint nova-api-validation-fw

Change-Id: I97a412aa23db75e3d892a113733e732eeb8008c1

commit_message:
Modify API ref for per-project-user quotas CRUD methods

**tenant** is an entity that owns the resources,
sometines called a project, sometimes the same as
a user

In addition to the owning entity (tenant), openstack
stores the entity performing the action as the **user**.

1st tenant ID in the URI, is the ID of the admin user
2ed tenant ID in the URI, is the project ID/Name
User ID is specified vis query string.
(I tried my best to express what I mean using the
current WADL markup.)

Changed the url path structure.
http://api.openstack.org/api-ref-compute.html#os-quota-sets

Changed the sample responses to point to the new ones in
/api_samples/os-user-quotas/

For the other part, in the original bug description:
Add commands for project user quotas management.
     - Show user quotas:
       nova-manage project quota --project <Project name>
       --user <User name>
     - Update/Create user quotas:
       nova-manage project quota --project <Project name>
       --user <User name> --key <key> --value <value>
I found this page:
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/NovaManage
"The nova-manage isn't properly documented, but it's going away
in Folsom, so using this wiki page for quick docs on it."

Looks like the usage of this method still needs further
validation, so dose the API call.
It may need to be futher documented in
docs.openstack.org/trunk/openstack-ops/content/quotas.html

Change-Id: I981e051dfb345a0213cb95b6f9dc1324e2e4a232
Closes-Bug: #1187277

commit_message:
Adds tenant_id to guest_info in heat code

Reasons:
- Heat code and used mysql/heat.template are missing tenant_id
- tenant_id is needed to simplify the identification of owner
  of the instance.

Changes:
- Adds tenant_id to heat.template and in heat code.

Change-Id: I08a8703e8d5f3db627a280c9df774d734437fcea
Closes-Bug: #1263159

commit_message:
Fix more regressions in contrib

Changes to contrib resources to use the new properties Schema caused
regressions in the Cloud LoadBalancer resource.

Change-Id: I46a19ef4b0248a6c60f11f963350975c6b86349c

commit_message:
Remove override of "patch" function

Overriding the patch method with an incompatable argument
list breaks contrib tests that used the version from
TestCase. This method was introduced in commit
3eda05a9b0b69803a0269f2aa344d14e5823bf6d but removing this
method does not affect other tests.

Change-Id: Iaecd171e5a548b2843b46e7c4b8ef48c52af6db6
Closes-Bug: 1263241

commit_message:
Enable parallel while deleting neutron resources

The confirm delete task was run immediately after creation in
handle_delete, which blocked the whole DependencyTaskGroup.
This patch gives other delete jobs a chance to run by stepping
the delete task in check_delete_complete.

Change-Id: I9ced21d3f98d949bd099bead27ac7b3e2d1090de

commit_message:
Introduce a way to trace a resource's implementation

We need a way to know whether a resource is really the
same during update. This is driven by TemplateResource
but not totally specific to it.

The problem is:
if you update a template with no changes (except for environment
or files changes) we need to know which resources to update.

This patch adds a "implementation_signature()" method that gives
us a mechanism to keep track of implementation changes like:
- a change in an environment mapping a resource to a new/different implementation
- a change in the content of a TemplateResource

And can distinguish between schema changes (requiring replacement) and
incremental changes (that can be updated in place).

Change-Id: I780074a827e3f51dede47a81f15e29dbe4d08804
Closes-bug: #1254966

commit_message:
Move the tests from functionalnosetests

Move the tests from functionalnosetests under functional, so we no
longer have two seperate trees for functional tests. This also drops
the 'nose' name from the directory, so that it doesn't end up with
confusion if we move to testr. Further, since there are no longer two
test runs in .functests, it nows looks very close to the other two.

Change-Id: I8de025c29d71f05072e257df24899927b82c1382

The magic is strong with this one.

How about we register the access keys with the stack, preferably along with a function to check the credentials, then do a dictionary lookup to find it. Seems much better than doing a linear search through all of the resources, then calling a magical function that does another linear search through all the resources before coming up with the access_allowed() function.

I too would like to see an example of how this is used, with a view to exorcising the magic altogether rather than making it worse."}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2013-11-28 19:17:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

The syntax easing that is suggested in the last paragraph of this commit message is basically a spec all on its own.

Agree about the scope of software config, and I would love to break it out into smaller tasks. This would happen quicker if I received some reviews on the WIP changes in this review topic.  Just about the general approach at this stage - there will be many changes as I get closer to be able to actually configure things.

Any self-contained change like this one I've broken out to the start of the series. revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-27 23:04:13.000000000', 'message': "Service authorize stack user from provided stack

Currently _authorize_stack_user requires that an EC2
keypair comes from an AccessKey resource (or some other resource
which uses the access_key as its resource_id).

This change avoids the separate db resource lookup, and checks
the provided stack for a resource which has an associated access_key.

This could be an AccessKey resource, or any resource which has an
access_key property, and an access_allowed method.

One of the objectives of hot-software-config is to reduce the
amount of template scaffolding required to enable software configuration.
This change means that an OS::Nova::Server resource wouldn't need
an associated OS::Heat::AccessPolicy, AWS::IAM::User, AWS::IAM::AccessKey
just so that os-collect-config can poll for metadata changes (note that
the actual change that does this for OS::Nova::Server is pending).

partial blueprint: hot-software-config

commit_message:
Service authorize stack user from provided stack

Currently _authorize_stack_user requires that an EC2
keypair comes from an AccessKey resource (or some other resource
which uses the access_key as its resource_id).

This change avoids the separate db resource lookup, and checks
the provided stack for a resource which has an associated access_key.

This could be an AccessKey resource, or any resource which has
registered an access allowed handler via register_access_allowed_handler.

Additionally, the credential_id does not have to be the AccessKey of a
keypair. credential_id could be any value meaningful to the resource
which registers the handler.

Since resources are lazy loaded, register_access_allowed_handler will not
be called until resources are loaded. This loading is triggered in
access_allowed by accessing the resources property.

One of the objectives of hot-software-config is to reduce the
amount of template scaffolding required to enable software configuration.
This change means that an OS::Nova::Server resource wouldn't need
an associated OS::Heat::AccessPolicy, AWS::IAM::User, AWS::IAM::AccessKey
just so that os-collect-config can poll for metadata changes (note that
the actual change that does this for OS::Nova::Server is pending).

partial blueprint: hot-software-config
Change-Id: I52a12ad3cd750ed724893abcd6dc1084b925c089

in Python 3.

commit_message:
Add volume total to Mgmt Instance Get

Add volume.total attribute and value to instance info returned by
mgmt show/get call in addition to volume.used.

This will help in validating cinder volume size reflects actual
filesystem size.

Change-Id: Ia89269edbf90b91967dedcc787dd54f8a56695de
Implements: blueprint add-volume-total-attribute

commit_message:
Delete control_exchange flag

control_exchange is duplicated in init.pp and ceilometer.pp which could
create duplicate declaration when declaring cinder and
cinder::ceilometer on same node.

Closes-bug #1266259

Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>
Change-Id: Ic1c5c880c421f43d2a125b2b5b58630fc55bc9c8
(cherry picked from commit bb977b42d526c7252817aca85dd2b350236111e8)

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-01-09 22:57:57.000000000', 'message': "Fix Migration 50e86cb2637a

The following migration 50e86cb2637a called
op.rename_table('neutron_nvp_port_mapping', 'neutron_nsx_port_mappings')
though the table name was actually quantum_nvp_port_mapping. Because of this
the quantum_id->nvp_id mapping was never migrated over to the new table and
you would be left with a quantum_nvp_port_mapping table hanging around.

In addition, the downgrade would rename the table to neutron_nvp_port_mapping
instead of quantum_nvp_port_mapping. This patch addresses this issues.

Change-Id: I56edb2f7821b51edaffa7182387513edc8bd66a3
"}]
commit_message:
Fix Migration 50e86cb2637a

The following migration 50e86cb2637a called
op.rename_table('neutron_nvp_port_mapping', 'neutron_nsx_port_mappings')
though the table name was actually quantum_nvp_port_mapping. Because of this
the quantum_id->nvp_id mapping was never migrated over to the new table and
you would be left with a quantum_nvp_port_mapping table hanging around.

In addition, the downgrade would rename the table to neutron_nvp_port_mapping
instead of quantum_nvp_port_mapping. This patch addresses this issues.

commit_message:
Translate the snapshot_pending state for old instances

Icehouse introduced an image_snapshot_pending state which Havana
compute nodes do not understand. This adds a translation for that
state when we are handling save() for a havana-era Instance object.

Closes-bug: #1265618
Change-Id: I36028defc3591cc6e31c7ba763a5c7f076832179

commit_message:
Prevent Instance.refresh() from returning a new info cache

If an older node does a refresh() on an instance, conductor will
return a new copy of the InstanceInfoCache, which the client
will balk at. Instead, add a refresh() method to info_cache and
call it from Instance.refresh().

Closes-bug: #1265607
Change-Id: I6a4787a23cd851cf56958c61f8b0559a79847ca0

commit_message:
Fix bug in validating Swift transaction ID

Currently Swift tests fail if a custom transaction ID with non-hex values is
used. This patch fixes this by modifying the regex.

Change-Id: Ia2cc9c81ee7875006e96c31bcd05e8b5069df3bf
Closes-Bug: #1262534

commit_message:
Introduce basic Pecan/WSME framework for KDS

So far there is simply a CLI application called kds-api that launches
the server using the reference wsgi server and a test just to
make sure things are wired in correctly.

blueprint: key-distribution-server
Change-Id: I17f1943eb6cd71f6059606a1a099f5761896b131

commit_message:
Create FK for parent_uuid on ALTER TABLE

Due to the fact that in MySQL a foreign key constraint requires indexes
for all involved fields it should be defined after these indexes.

The backref definition was corrected for the parent relationship.

Change-Id: I891af2cf6efbcb401c6a2c38e65c8aaf22d171b0

commit_message:
Add support for VMDK driver

The patch adds support for VMware vmdk cinder driver. It also
supports configuring the driver for multi-backend scenarios.

implements blueprint support-vmdk-driver

Change-Id: I3f50f9974100ceab2a991f692022dd918f2e4445

commit_message:
Prevent dictionary size from changing while iterating over its items

In Python 3, dict.items() returns 'a dict_item'. Iterating over it while
deleting some of the dictionary elements is forbidden. We have to iterate over
a list to avoid getting this error:

    RuntimeError: dictionary changed size during iteration

Change-Id: I43401e6eb9a31148fda4677644bf99e1b739d0dd

commit_message:
Drop large-ops test down to 50 instances from 100

It turns out the variance in cloud instances is very high, especially
when comparing different cloud providers and regions. This test was
originally added as a regression test for the nova-network issues with
rootwrap. At which time this test wouldn't pass for 30 instances.  So 50
is still a valid regression test.

Change-Id: I20a158cdd043d53be0b96437826559a71f7698bf

commit_message:
Fix ceilometer collector dispatcher on SLES

Follow the guide on SLES SP3 without ceilometer collector dispatcher
configured, it will print nothing when verify with
`ceilometer meter-list`, because the ceilometer-collector catches an
exception of `RuntimeError: No ceilometer.dispatcher extensions found`

This patch add a step for SLES to configure default ceilometer
collector dispatcher to `database`.

Change-Id: Ib2dade0a6f382ec43eac64374e5977df81a48b61
Closes-Bug: #1267318

commit_message:
Move six to the right location

Third party imports are supposed to be after standard library imports
so make six be after. Some newlines are also added to separate
standard library imports from all the others.

Co-authored-by: Ivan A. Melnikov <imelnikov@griddynamics.com>
Change-Id: Ied067e9367612758666da726df195ed390215e1b

commit_message:
Fix typo in test

A single-char typo in test_auth caused a value that should have
been a simple string into a tuple of strings. This made the test
generate what's actually invalid input data since the username
is supposed to be a simple string.

Change-Id: I7a477bb8e5504c1c7982cf56ffe69e1c5294cadf
Related-bug: #1265108

[{'created': '2014-01-01 14:24:48.000000000', 'message': 'Update log message for scale out/in

When create two stacks with same template with autoscaling group,
then when scale out/in, the log message would be as
(HadoopSlaveScaleUpPolicy is my scale up alarm and HadoopSGroup is
my autoscaling group):

HadoopSlaveScaleUpPolicy Alarm, adjusting Group HadoopSGroup by 1

From above log message, I do not know which stack is being scaled up.

This patch add scale group id to the log message so that we can know
which group is being scale out/in.

Change-Id: Ie4862e9738c652b813b3dae01f9aeb3557e79b9a
Closes-Bug: #1265315
'}]
commit_message:
Update log message for scale out/in

When create two stacks with same template with autoscaling group,
then when scale out/in, the log message would be as
(HadoopSlaveScaleUpPolicy is my scale up alarm and HadoopSGroup is
my autoscaling group):

HadoopSlaveScaleUpPolicy Alarm, adjusting Group HadoopSGroup by 1

From above log message, I do not know which stack is being scaled up.

This patch add scale group id to the log message so that we can know
which group is being scale out/in.

Change-Id: Ie4862e9738c652b813b3dae01f9aeb3557e79b9a
Closes-Bug: #1265315

commit_message:
chore: Sync local (marconi) requirements with global reqs

This gets us the latest Falcon, with its associated bug fixes, esp. wrt
accept header parsing.

Also fixed some hacking violations to get this to pass the gate.

Change-Id: Ic7bfc8210947f37078d034fc2f56cc04b2d88392

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-01-06 06:52:48.000000000', 'message': 'Fix glanceclient http.py string formatting error

* Proposed fixes of "TypeError: not all arguments converted during string
formatting" are:
a) msg = 'Unable to load CA from "%s" %s' % (self.cacert, e)

b) msg = 'Unable to load CA from "{0}" {1}'.format(self.cacert, e)

or if the original author intend to use tuple to format the msg
c) msg = 'Unable to load CA from "%s"' % ((self.cacert, e),)

I prefer fix b), .format one, however consider L431, L416, I use a) to align
with those.

* Add a UT case to cover the path where the bug is in, then the original
version cannot pass UT until it is fixed in this bug.

* During fixing the bug, I find that pep8 and flake8 won't report such string
format error, at least by default settings, but pylint can
pylint http.py | grep "format string"
E:438,22:VerifiedHTTPSConnection.setcontext: Too many arguments for format
string
So I suggest the community use editor with pylint integrated for static
analysis. Mine is vim + scrooloose/syntastic(which will use pylint for python
by default). Eclipse also has pylint plugin.

Change-Id: I91a137c5c3a9a3cc603804bef5eaea14ae281c08
Closes-Bug: #1265730
'}, {'created': '2014-01-07 03:42:34.000000000', 'message': 'Fix glanceclient http.py string formatting error

* Proposed fixes of "TypeError: not all arguments converted during string
formatting" are:
a) msg = 'Unable to load CA from "%s" %s' % (self.cacert, e)

b) msg = 'Unable to load CA from "{0}" {1}'.format(self.cacert, e)

or if the original author intend to use tuple to format the msg
c) msg = 'Unable to load CA from "%s"' % ((self.cacert, e),)

I prefer fix b), .format one, however consider L431, L416, I use a) to align
with those.

[Change after review]:
Zhi Yan Liu and Fei Long Wang give me comments on string formatting flavor,
and suggest the dict way
d) msg = 'Unable to load CA from "%(cacert)s" %(exc)s' %
dict(cacert=self.cacert, exc=e)
One reason is that when multiple varibles are needed to
substitute, this way can mitigate risk of disordered assignment. So I'll change
in d) way. And I have no time to study the performance comparison among these 4
options.

* Add a UT case to cover the path where the bug is in, then the original
version cannot pass UT until it is fixed in this bug.

* During fixing the bug, I find that pep8 and flake8 won't report such string
format error, at least by default settings, but pylint can
pylint http.py | grep "format string"
E:438,22:VerifiedHTTPSConnection.setcontext: Too many arguments for format
string
So I suggest the community use editor with pylint integrated for static
analysis. Mine is vim + scrooloose/syntastic(which will use pylint for python
by default). Eclipse also has pylint plugin.

Change-Id: I91a137c5c3a9a3cc603804bef5eaea14ae281c08
Closes-Bug: #1265730

commit_message:
Fix glanceclient http.py string formatting error

* Fix "TypeError: not all arguments converted during string formatting"

* Add a UT case to cover the path where the bug is in

Change-Id: I91a137c5c3a9a3cc603804bef5eaea14ae281c08
Closes-Bug: #1265730

Ubuntu PPA packages are missing quantum-ovs-cleanup
service scripts whereas RHEL et al set this service up
appropriately on package installation.

This update addresses the missing service by installing
the upstart configuration and setting it to start at the

l3 agent and dhcp agents.

For additional details, see:

commit_message:
Bugfix missing quantum-ovs-cleanup on startup

Ubuntu PPA packages are missing quantum-ovs-cleanup
service scripts whereas RHEL et al set this service up
appropriately on package installation.

This update addresses the missing service by installing
the upstart configuration and setting it to start at the
appropriate point in the bootup process, prior to the
l3 agent and dhcp agents.

For additional details, see:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/openstack-manuals/+bug/1156861

Change-Id: Id8abcc07ad3c0b0cfd742886a2f3d71d16585d91
Fixes-Bug: #1266495

commit_message:
Update spec_helper to include 'chefspec/berkshelf'

This minor change allows you to run rspec outside of strainer while
still having cookbook dependencies automatically handled by berkshelf
(which also means you can run individual chefspec tests).

Note that this change does marginally increase the time it takes to run
a strainer test.

A similar change was recently accepted in the openstack-compute
cookbook.

Change-Id: Ifbe179fbb62b7bf487e090db2c2a367d1f7cee73

commit_message:
Update spec_helper to include 'chefspec/berkshelf'

This minor change allows you to run rspec outside of strainer while
still having cookbook dependencies automatically handled by berkshelf
(which also means you can run individual chefspec tests).

Note that this change does marginally increase the time it takes to run
a strainer test.

A similar change was recently accepted in the openstack-compute
cookbook.

Change-Id: I3cb98dd54675d9ff2bff340425378b34b021d9da

commit_message:
Fixes wrong variable invoking during get transport

Now the method of transport() of queues/v1/client.py is invoking
wrong variable name. This patch fixes it and add an unit test.

NOTE: More unit test cases for v1/client.py will be added in a
separate patch.

Change-Id: I75a2498002bb2b9b7475bef0af5eebc8d82d662d
Closes-Bug: #1266467

'}, {'account_id': 7156, 'date': '2014-01-09 00:18:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

What was the original ownership and mode?

This should already be handled (correctly) by the packaging."}, {'account_id': 9061, 'date': '2014-01-09 16:15:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Good point.

/var/cache/swift is created by the python-swift package.
In grizzly (1.8), this package creates /var/cache/swift as root.root in 0755.
In havana (1.10), the package creates /var/cache/swift as root.swift in 0775.
https://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/swift/+bug/1234657

So this would only need to be in the stable/grizzly branch, not havana.'}, {'account_id': 9061, 'date': '2014-01-09 16:24:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Abandoned

Abandoning this change, I will submit a new changed based against stable/grizzly - not master.'}]

commit_message:
Add /var/cache/swift to the list of directories that must be owned by swift.

/var/cache/swift must be writeable by the user swift.

Change-Id: I6de68e23d4bd3804c0a2630034e6bba882e91bc8

commit_message:
Adding pagination support for backups

* add a _pagination method to base Manager
* switched existing paginated list to use the new method
* removed description from backup list and added updated

Implements: blueprint paginate-backup-list

'}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2014-01-05 23:39:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

This is a known problem and there has been a lot of discussion recently around how to handle the situation where we have simultaneous v2 and v3 endpoints. ayoung has a patch on here that is trying to do something very similar, and i have some other ideas i'm working towards. 

We've previously decided that changing the service identifier is not a good way to approach the problem, but it may be something we should allow in the short term anyway. The flow on effects of this though would mean needing to add the service_type to the CLI which i think is a bad idea. 

I'd appreciate some others waying in. So far i'm thinking that how to manage the service catalog and multiple versions of endpoint is a summit session - but that was because i was expecting that i would be the one to do it and i didn't see there being time before then. 

Have a look at the auth_plugin reviews, this won't work with them, but if anything it may become slightly easier. 

Also ping be on irc: jamielennox and we can talk about what's been happening in this area"}, {'account_id': 8996, 'date': '2014-01-06 10:17:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

I understand (and agree) that there is (theoretically) no reason to have different service identifiers associated with different API versions of the same service.

However, a mechanism allowing the user to choose the API version (and endpoints associated with) he wishes to use would be very useful (and ease the transition from one version of the API to the other). And right now, I think that the "service type" trick, consisting in having a service type per API version, is the easiest and quickest (and not so dirty) way to provide such feature (this has already been done with the cinder client)..

In the long run, I would be glad to help in finding a nicer solution.
I'll try and catch you on the IRC (my nick is florentflament).'}, {'account_id': 8996, 'date': '2014-01-06 10:21:26.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 5494, 'date': '2014-01-06 10:21:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

versioned service types is an anti-pattern that i *really* don't want to see keystone advocating or supporting in any manner"}, {'account_id': 8996, 'date': '2014-01-08 21:40:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Well, I understand your point of view.

However, I would like to set an Openstack platform, where I would have some clients using the Identity v3 API, while others would use the v2 API. I believe that such a feature would help Openstack users in progressively adopting the Identity v3 API.

How would you do without exposing one service type per API version ?

May I suggest that we adopt such an anti-pattern in a first time to allow using both v2 and v3 APIs together, then improve the implementation to keep the feature while doing it the right way ?

I would be glad to contribute to such an improvement.'}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2014-01-09 00:31:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Florent: The situation we've been discussing is that you should specify the root unversioned endpoint in the service catalog. So when you need to talk to a compute endpoint you query the catalog then ask that endpoint what versions it supports.

There are obviously some issues with this in terms of performance and caching, but some of the work i am doing around auth plugins and the catalog are looking to fix this.  

@Dolph: I'm also thinking that putting a version number in the service catalog itself is going to be necessary for the transition process and possibly as an optimisation."}, {'account_id': 8996, 'date': '2014-01-09 08:21:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I agree that it would make sense to have root unversioned endpoints in the service catalog. Although, this would require updating the current implementation for retrieving endpoints. Still, we would probably need a way to do a smooth transition.'}, {'account_id': 866, 'date': '2014-01-09 09:10:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I agree that we should not go in the business to differentiate between v2 and v3 but the patch it itself to allow specify another service_type name than 'identity' may be useful if the operator want to use an another name for whatever reasons (i.e: i18n)"}, {'account_id': 8996, 'date': '2014-01-09 16:03:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Abandoned

Seen on IRC with Dolph, Keystone's catalog should provide a unique, unversionned set of endpoints per service. It should not have a service type per API version. The hardcoded 'identity' service type will be kept."}]

commit_message:
Fix identity endpoints when exposing both v2 and v3 APIs

When both v2 and v3 Identity (Keystone) APIs are available, Keystone
client needs a way to find the appropriate endpoints. Prior to this
patch both v2 and v3 clients looked for the ``identity`` service type,
which didn't allow to have different endpoints for these two APIs.

This fix adds a ``service_type`` keyword argument to the
``keystoneclient.v3.client.Client`` constructor, allowing to choose
the ``service_type`̀ to use for the Keystone v3 API (for instance
``identityv3``). The default value is `identity`, so that the default
behavior remains unchanged.

Change-Id: Idbae937b5a7af3324ea7f90b500da88ef670e409

commit_message:
Add initial image-* commands to CLI

list - provides a list of registered images
show - provides details of a given registered image
register - registers an image available from the glance index
unregister - unregister a registered image
add-tag - add a tag to a registered image
remove-tag - remove a tag from a registered image

Change-Id: Ideaf6b4e166754ab1581bc76bd83a4a25966ab55
Implements: blueprint python-savannaclient-cli

commit_message:
Fixes a link to the wrong page for DHCP agent install

A previous patch added a link for further assistance during the
DHCP agent installation section of the Neutron single-flat use-case.
Unfortunately, the document it refers to is the one for the controller
and not the network node as required.

This patch updates the recently merged document to represent the
correct page. The backport will also be rectified before merge.

Change-Id: I4996804344bb29b10c7b07a8800ca2c1a6410b00

commit_message:
Updates single flat use-case example for RHEL/CentOS/Fedora

Adds specific configuration options for RHEL, CentOS and Fedora
based distributions which were missing - e.g. the guide presumed
RabbitMQ was in use despite it not being relevant for these
platforms. In addition it adds clarity on where to find further
information or how to complete a specific step where necessary,
something the existing implementation lacked.

Now uses openstack-config in RHEL and SUSE based platforms.

Change-Id: I6c9a45114afbfa99ea2d01a3f682a0dc78a72530

> Overall, there's methods related to stacks all nested, but then validate_template and resource_types are outside of stacks, is that the intent?

Yes, because it returns the list of resource types supported by the service (not the stack), e.g:

GET v1/?{tenant_id}?/resource_types

Whereas all of the stuff nested under stacks is

v1/?{tenant_id}?/stacks/...

commit_message:
Pass UUID to add_instance_fault_from_exc instead of instance

Part of the blueprint: icehouse-objects. This will be used by the
scheduler code that is moving to obejcts.

The instance UUID will passed to the method instead of the reference
to the instance.

commit_message:
Set KVM usage false by defualt

As temporary fix to get instances Active,
we need use qemu in sys tests
Change KVM_USE value in setting.py by default
false value, if os environ is not defined
Add else part in fuel_web client to
verify if KVMS_USE false, update OS setting to qemu

Change-Id: Ifc817104d6b8a6d3a5de27c10c07afcdc92f283f

commit_message:
Database fixture

The fixture manages a real SQLalchemy database that gets created and
upgraded using the same process as in production. This was not done
previously because running the upgrades before every test takes a
prohibitively long time.  The fixture avoids this by upgrading the
database only once and storing the upgraded database in a golden file.
The golden file is restored after every test.

This patchset modifies the base TestCase to use the new fixture. This
tests the storage:sqlalchemy plugin. Other test cases (specifically, the
PowerDNS backend) will be modified to use the fixture in later
patchsets.

Change-Id: Ib8f6274d50cf7157f7383bba14b71fac1ff32ce7

commit_message:
Correct SSHPowerDriver validate() exceptions

Driver valdiate() method should raise only InvalidParameterValue
exceptions, which will be caught by
ConductorManager.validate_driver_interfaces().

The SSH driver was potentially raising a FileNotFound exception which
would be unhandled. This patch converts that into InvalidParamterValue.

Change-Id: I82d9776206c1391ba151614ac7512865f8ea672c

Lost a lot of time because I couldn't do the rebase/merge. I guess I have to work on my git-fu.

I experimented with the container CPU weight. 

I started one container A without explicit CPU shares configured (default 0). 
I started another container B with 1 cpu share. 

It turns out that the container A will consume in this scenario >90% if the CPU time. 

If start container B with 1024 CPU shares then both container will consume 50% of the CPU time.

I found following config files:
/sys/fs/cgroup/lxc/cpu.shares = 1024
/sys/fs/cgroup/cpu.shares = 1024

Those files also suggest that 1024 is good magic number for CPU shares.
However I tried to change the value of this files to see if it has a effect (same testing as above but different value e.g. 512). It turns out that changes in this files do not affect the default value of docker."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-05 10:24:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Doesn't seem to work

[{'created': '2013-12-03 20:36:10.000000000', 'message': "Docker Driver doesn't respect CPU limit

The docker driver doesn't respect the CPU settings of the configured
flavor.

Docker/LXC supports only relative cpu allocation. The relative
cpu allocation doesn't prevent that a container can use all CPUs but it
can at least ensure that a container with more CPUs gets more CPU
cycles.

Change-Id: I7184eddfd8bbd2cbaa07a48ebb40bc9aa3fbd4a9

commit_message:
Docker Driver doesn't respect CPU limit

The docker driver doesn't respect the CPU settings of the configured
flavor.

Docker/LXC supports only relative cpu allocation. The relative
cpu allocation doesn't prevent that a container can use all CPUs but it
can at least ensure that a container with more CPUs gets more CPU
cycles.

DocImpact - Docker containers are now given CPU shares according to
the vcpu setting of the flavor used when creating the container.
Previously, the vcpu field was ignored and all containers got equal
CPU shares, regardless of the vcpu setting.

Change-Id: I7184eddfd8bbd2cbaa07a48ebb40bc9aa3fbd4a9
Closes-Bug: #1256264

commit_message:
nova-api should check UTF8 char in parameters

Enter the instance name when you create a new instance. If you enter the instance name in particular unicode, an
error will occur. This error clear a list of all the instances in the dashboard. Therefore, I fixed to allow any
type.

Fixes : bug #940430

Change-Id: I2af958370e6ededf2ac81b6416b96abae0072d5e

commit_message:
Python 3: use six.iteritems() instead of iteritems()

Six.iteritems() replaces dictionary.iteritems() on Python 2 and
dictionary.items() on Python 3.

Change-Id: I9a83090e75ad98c4e6bbfdaf2236884dcef4bd96

[{'created': '2014-01-07 16:54:34.000000000', 'message': 'Check for pep8 E226 and E24

By default, pep8.py ignores E226 and E24. By changing
tox.ini to not have an ignore clause, it started using
the default. Since we were explicitely ignoring things
until recently, E226 and E24 where being checked. This
patch adds an ignore clause to tox.ini and fixes some
E226 errors to match our pep8 checks to other projects
in openstack.

Change-Id: Ia0bc0e6bcb4b4c6e54d61bae2fd7cad48303a62a
'}]
commit_message:
Check for pep8 E226 and E24

By default, pep8.py ignores E226 and E24. By changing
tox.ini to not have an ignore clause, it started using
the default. Since we were explicitely ignoring things
until recently, E226 and E24 where being checked. This
patch adds an ignore clause to tox.ini and fixes some
E226 errors to match our pep8 checks to other projects
in openstack.

Change-Id: Ia0bc0e6bcb4b4c6e54d61bae2fd7cad48303a62a

commit_message:
Cleanup object usage in the rebuild path

This patch removes a redundant fetch of instance system_metadata
that was used to refresh our notion since the first get. Now that
the rest of the code is using instance.save(), it has an updated
view of system_metadata at effectively the same point.

Related to blueprint icehouse-objects

Change-Id: I357daa5ae627e8959b77bd0cb00e152810f9c0eb

commit_message:
Add run_test.sh for running tests

This is a copy of the test entry point used in Nova, Swift, Keystone,
Tuskar, Glance, Horizon, Neutron, Heat, Cinder, and others. It
provides a simple way to add consistency and repeatability to running
tests w/ minimal human effort, just run ./run_tests.sh.

Change-Id: I7d9369f7c86b62a6e7ba9b66344d6ad25596251f

commit_message:
Get rid of unnecessary log from node validation

ConductorManager.validate_driver_interfaces unnecessarily logs all
InvalidParameterValue exceptions raised by driver's validate methods,
so it should be removed.

Change-Id: Iccb4fa60ec5b96097ac7232ad4502aca14f492a8
Closes-Bug: #1263210

commit_message:
Remove ununsed httplib2 requirement

This is not needed anymore since the logging is handled by
six.moves/httplib.

Change-Id: I4315860648258fb760ea22ca09d0083d7c9afb6c
Closes-Bug: #1266584

commit_message:
Enable deleting multiple stacks with single call

Now "heat stack-delete" can only delete one stack in one request,
this patch enhances this command to allow deletion of multiple
stacks with single call.

Change-Id: Id48bfdbbcd565435725c8a4adf1196dcbb93f9df
Closes-Bug: #1256971

commit_message:
Remove vim header

Vim settings can be done in your vimrc file, there is no need to add
them in each source files. Also if set incorrectly, gate (pep8 check)
will catch your mistakes.

NOTE: openstack.common files are left untouched because they should be
fixed in oslo.

Change-Id: I96fe6479e64a13766e7a974727405423a66cd496
Closes-Bug: #1229324

commit_message:
Validate number of instance metadata entries

The Server resource arbitrarily limits instance metadata to five
entries, when the actual provider's maxServerMeta limit could be much
higher.  Make the Server resource check the provider's maxServerMeta
absolute limit and enforce that limit in validate().

Change-Id: Ic00fc6f3a41ae783e43bd7f2df8663263d9cbf90
Closes-Bug: #1260427

commit_message:
Avoid error on double-delete of nested stack

When deleting a stack that has a nested stack previously deleted, the
process fails because the nested stack cannot be retrieved from the
database.
To solve the bug, the nested stack is now retrieved from the database
ignoring the deleted stacks before the deletion process begins. Then
a NotFound exception is raised, and then when it's catched the nested
stack will be ignored.

Change-Id: Ib863527dbfb0200b833a4e90b5a4fd50f469c1ce
Closes-Bug: #1261436

commit_message:
support deploy again for previous failed deployment

Current code behaviour does not allow to deploy again if the provision
state is "deploy failed", and for such internal field, user can not
update by API/CLI, so we should allow to deploy again.

Change-Id: I61d8ea850556c5f5375a33257155855519027c71
Closes-Bug: #1266189

commit_message:
Implement single (non-scalable) engine

 * New engine for running workflow (w/o rabbit)
 * Engine constructs a workflow
 * REST API action
 * AMQP action (not finished)
 * Task and execution state update
 * Added unit tests for this engine

Partially implements blueprint: mistral-poc
Partially implements blueprint: mistral-workflow-execution

Change-Id: I0e2b1a25f4281f77dad07a6f5241025be0963ed7

commit_message:
Fix systemctl problem on SLES in ceilometer setup

There is a problem when enable mongodb service on SLES in ceilometer
install section, which uses `systemctl start mongodb.service`.

systemctl is not installed in SLES SP3 by default, and
mongodb.service is not a valid service too. This patch uses common
commands of `service` and `chkconfig` to do the right job.

Change-Id: I3d44f6aba155601030b9b13dc7ef29550e19dc2c
Closes-Bug: #1267297

commit_message:
Add new meters for swift

    This patch adds new meters:
        -storage.containers.objects
        -storage.containers.objects.size.
    These meters are implemented through a polling Swift

blueprint: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Ceilometer/blueprints/pollster-swift

Change-Id: Ic1f3aaf351db0b99392eb13d4f31f2732f87f816

commit_message:
Clean up location when the quota limit is reached

When the quota limit is reached, the image location is not cleaned
up. At the point the location should be deleted since the image
data upload didn't succeed and the store should have already
cleaned up the patially uploaded dada.

Change-Id: I1311c967c29c4b83d129095fe94a90b83908c305

commit_message:
Fix configuring libvirt before installation

When enabling nova::migration::libvirt, it will try to configure
libvirtd.conf before installing libvirt package. This patchset adds
a dependency to make sure libvirt package has been installed when
running nova::migration::libvirt.

Change-Id: I981217c2bbecb276f25fa98d897e1da93d7e02a7
Closes-bug: #1254372

Fix MultiNode_DevStack template

The ComputeNodes parameter has to be changed to String instead of a
Number otherwise the UserData property cannot be resolved properly.

Change-Id: I9ddb9154c380f1d0aa1cf47e7bb646a304e59e68

commit_message:
Improve the node driver interfaces validation output

This patch improves the output of the node driver interfaces validation
to return the reason why the interface failed to validate.

The new structure looks like:

{'deploy':  {'result': True},
 'power':   {'result': False, 'reason': 'Invalid IPMI username'},
 'console': {'result': None, 'reason': 'not supported'},
 'rescue':  {'result': None, 'reason': 'not supported'}}

The patch also remove an unneeded log that was logging the errors for
each interface, every time the validation was called.

Change-Id: Id5d8aa1bd150b7d85f359471daccfacb6d9e2ede
Closes-Bug: #1263210

commit_message:
Use bash in mysql element install script.

We now call the mysql element's install.d script with bash, since it is
using non-POSIX shell features (specifically, [[ and regex matching).

Change-Id: I8cc22dbe2df9c30925cb9dfd850bbe3d06f30f2a

commit_message:
Add set_provision_state to the client libs

The commit https://review.openstack.org/#/c/61160/ exposes in the Ironic
API a way to trigger the provisioning of a node. This patch add this
functionality on the client libraries (Not exposed on the CLI).

Change-Id: I8c0f339f2c76c153ecba961d0ca411d438c21ceb

commit_message:
Delete iSCSI devices after volume detached

Previously, after detaching from a volume, the iSCSI device
remains attached on the compute node until all LUNs for a given
IQN are detached -- causing issues when LUNs are reused for
different volumes. This change will delete the device(s)
associated with the detached volume so LUNs can be reused.

Fixes bug 1112483
Change-Id: Icae3ec4d1ee2036fbba7b9eb5c03a1c86014fcc0

commit_message:
Fixed sphinx ERRORs.

Fixed errors and warnings due to formatting and layout errors
in documentation.
Those errors makes the page be empty or unavailable.
Other layouts/format fixes makes documentation more clear.

Removed rpc/common.py from patch as suggested in code review.

[{'created': '2014-01-07 17:03:50.000000000', 'message': 'Create swift operator keystone roles

Defining operator_roles in swift-proxy.conf requires
that these roles exist in keystone.

Because Keystone API access is not available on Swift
proxy hosts in most cases, operator_roles keystone
roles have been added to swift::keystone::auth class.

Added basic docs for swift::keystone::auth

Change-Id: Ib8454f8ae1316d2589ff228ec1424c6cff69c6b5
Closes-Bug: #1261662
(cherry picked from commit 14a2bd8c4fdad27fe708792c8a040c55a7476c56)
'}]
commit_message:
Create swift operator keystone roles

Defining operator_roles in swift-proxy.conf requires
that these roles exist in keystone.

Because Keystone API access is not available on Swift
proxy hosts in most cases, operator_roles keystone
roles have been added to swift::keystone::auth class.

Added basic docs for swift::keystone::auth

Change-Id: Ib8454f8ae1316d2589ff228ec1424c6cff69c6b5
Closes-Bug: #1261662
(cherry picked from commit 14a2bd8c4fdad27fe708792c8a040c55a7476c56)

commit_message:
Remove 'disable user' logic from _delete_domain_contents

Bug 1130236 has been marked as completed and fix released. This
commit removes the logic in `_delete_domain_contents` that disabled
the users prior to cleaning up the contents of the domain due to the
bug.

Change-Id: I0b1fba429cf45baae88a629e1629ce704dad4246

commit_message:
Break dependency of base V3Controller on V2Controller

With the cleanup that has occured, it is now possible to make the
V3Controller to stand on its own with out needing to inherit from
the V2Controller. To accomodate this change, `_require_attribute`
has been moved from V2Controller to keystone.common.wsgi.Application.

Change-Id: Id5cd5384a100a5d3de6beac2ba445854a2e8e6fd

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-23 06:11:01.000000000', 'message': 'Move deletion business logic out of controllers

Based upon the feedback on the credential_api deletion changes,
the deletion code should be moved down to the managers from the
controllers. This means the business logic to delete / modify
associated resources based upon an given action no longer resides
in the controller. The changes include (but are not limited to)
mass token deletion (delete_tokens_for_(user|trust|project|domain),
domain content deletion, credential deletion, etc.

This change also moves around the use of @dependancy decorator
to ensure the *_api managers are added to the correct objects.

The token_api has been expanded to handle the token revocations
for users, projects, and domains directly (public methods). This
allows the managers to handle deletions rather than the
logic residing in the controllers; it was previously not clean
to issue a `delete_tokens_for_user` outside of the controller.

A few minor test changes and additions were needed to handle the
moving of business logic. Notably, the keystoneclient tests
(test_keystoneclient) CompatTestCase needs to setup SQL for the
credential_api to be able to perform delete logic. The test for
identity_api.list_users_in_group has been updated to verify it
is possible to get an empty list back when/if the group is
empty (previously LDAP backend would raise an exception).

bp: assignment-controller-first-class
Change-Id: I721e49258c10830b3c44f301e8c9e5f954262388

commit_message:
Move deletion business logic out of controllers

Based upon the feedback on the credential_api deletion changes,
the deletion code should be moved down to the managers from the
controllers. This means the business logic to delete / modify
associated resources based upon a given action no longer resides
in the controller. The changes include (but are not limited to)
mass token deletion (delete_tokens_for_(user|trust|project|domain),
domain content deletion, credential deletion, etc.

This change also moves around the use of @dependency decorator
to ensure the *_api managers are added to the correct objects.

The token_api has been expanded to handle the token revocations
for users, projects, and domains directly (public methods). This
allows the managers to handle deletions rather than the
logic residing in the controllers; it was previously not clean
to issue a `delete_tokens_for_user` outside of the controller.

A few minor test changes and additions were needed to handle the
moving of business logic. Notably, the keystoneclient tests
(test_keystoneclient) CompatTestCase needs to setup SQL for the
credential_api to be able to perform delete logic.

bp: assignment-controller-first-class
Change-Id: I721e49258c10830b3c44f301e8c9e5f954262388

commit_message:
Do not update password when updating grants in Assignment KVS

Assignment KVS backend no longer performs an update that causes
the user's password to be updated when updating grants. This
potentially would have caused any/all grant updates to set the
user's password to the current password hash, effectively making
it impossible to login with the user. The longer-term fix
should ensure that the backend does not need to update the user
itself from the driver level.

Change-Id: I74ffc643020fa077c39a0cf16847e397a0c24139
Closes-bug: #1265887

commit_message:
Cleanup of new credential_api delete methods

Based upon the feedback on the credential_api.delete_credentials_for_user
and credential_api.delete_credentials_for_project implementations, apply
some cleaner default logic and comments/docstrings.

Change-Id: I6d1abe71931bce82c122d6cce9a94beccd8ffcfb
bp: assignment-controller-first-class

commit_message:
Enhance list_group_users in GroupApi.

If there is no member in the group.
When get the group users, the varible "member" is an empty dictionary.
It will crash at "member[self.member_attribute]".
This commit add a judgment to determine the member is empty or not.

Closes-Bug: #1259426
Change-Id: Ic20549204bcc35f71464b858f5ca900a4bbfe049

commit_message:
Whitelist external netaddr requirement

* tox.ini(testenv.install_command): Use the --allow-external and
--allow-insecure options so that pip 1.5 and later will assent to
retrieve the netaddr package even though it's not hosted on PyPI.
The --allow-insecure option is aliased to a clearer
--allow-unverified wording in 1.5, but the old form is being used to
avoid breaking users of 1.4.x and will be valid at least through
1.6.x according to comments in the pip source.

Partial-Bug: #1266513

Change-Id: I005e752c8cb9bca78b1ebe777eb5230e9bf05bd8

Actually, it's not.

Reposting my comment from https://review.openstack.org/#/c/61663:

ML2 plugin needs 'agents' table to exist (at least when OVS agent is used), but according to what was stated in migrations_for_plugins list of 511471cc46b_agent_ext_model_supp.py it must not have been created, but in fact it was (this is how it passed the gate tests), because we've had LBaaS service plugin enabled, for which that migrations has been applied.

My migration changing agents table triggered this issue to be seen in devstack runs when neutron is used without LBaaS service plugin. Yong's patch fixes this.

But without Yong's patch ML2 must have been broken (as it still needs that table), but it wasn't. So it seems to me that we have code that calls metadata.create_all() which creates missing agents table when neutron-server starts.

Giving this fact, it's OK to change those migrations scripts. Even though they haven't been applied when ML2 was used, tables were created."}, {'account_id': 6849, 'date': '2013-12-13 17:03:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Mark, continuing our chat in IRC... 

after thinking about this once again... trunk users: if they are using ML2 now - they have agents table created, fixing of this migrations will be no-op for them and that's ok; released code users - we provide fixed migrations in a point release, agents table already exists in their databases, migrations will be no-op and that's ok, new installations of both will use fixed migrations scripts. So even if security settings were modified, it would not cause us problems, as we don't need to create new tables here  - we just need to fix new installations and do nothing for existing ones (regardless if it's trunk or a released version). So my point is - they all already have that table, if they didn't ML2, wouldn't work at all. I totally agree that we must not edit existing migrations scripts, but in this particular case it seems to be harmless. If I'm not missing something"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-13 19:30:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified

commit_message:
Add L3 service in service_plugins param

This service plugin implements the L3 routing functionality (resources
router and floatingip) that in earlier releases before Havana was provided by
core plugins (openvswitch, linuxbridge, ... etc).

Core plugins can now choose not to implement L3 routing functionality
and instead delegate that to the L3 routing service plugin.

This patch aims to add the new service in the param documentation.

Change-Id: I03fe52706f2857d42baf01db8362804c597f5155
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

commit_message:
engine_life_check_timeout support

Since https://github.com/openstack/heat/commit/d7ae961fcae5e0e75bf232606a6878d2414dfeef
got merged, heat engine has now a distributed stack lock using the
database to avoid race conditions when multiple engines are deployed.

This patch aims to add a new flag to configure the RPC timeout for the
engine liveness check that is used for stack locking.

Change-Id: Iad7958225651e2b52844b5d942f6630bbe9e86fa
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

commit_message:
Python 3: use six.iteritems() instead of iteritems()

Six.iteritems() replaces dictionary.iteritems() on Python 2 and
dictionary.items() on Python 3.

Change-Id: I1588d92a9384497a65d1ea3530f8143e7953ed95

commit_message:
Add python-swift client to the requirements

Since Id4b27ee70f420f7536b4c698eb1f3bba15dbd1e8 we have swift scenarios tests
which means that we must include swiftclient as a requirement.
Closes-bug: #1265936

commit_message:
Add support for kick-starting new datastores

The datastore type and version config settings are now
parameterized to allow any datastore.
The only missing information for new datastores
is the list of packages to install on the instance.

The datastore already supported by kick-start
(mysql, redis, percona) have been given default packages.
Packages for supported datastores can be overwritten by
setting the $PACKAGES variable before running cmd_set_datastore().

Change-Id: I72a715ea460e74e870a3385b753da9d8ad1411aa
co-authored-by: Kevin Conway <kevinjacobconway@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Remove plugin_name_v2 and extension_manager in test_config

There are two ways to specify a core plugin and an extension manager
in the unit tests: test_config and arguments of the constructor.
Both are used and it sometimes makes it a bit difficult to debug.
This patch removes the way via test_config and makes constructor
arguments the only way to do it.

Also removes the default entries in test_config because they are
not used anywhere.

Change-Id: I491003f4246e62001e9b74743c8fbfa922088383
Closes-Bug: #1245335

commit_message:
Don't deallocate/reallocate networks on reschedules

If network allocation is not host dependent we don't need to deallocate
and reallocate a network for each reschedule.  Only baremetal has host
dependent allocation so for that driver networks are de/reallocated on a
reschedule.

The current method in the code which checks for the length of the list
returned from _get_instance_nw_info() doesn't work because it can't
distinguish between an unallocated network and one that doesn't return
network information.

Part of bp remove-cast-to-schedule-run-instance

Change-Id: Ic427715f46cb5179a37c593c4217f239c65544c3

[{'account_id': 2468, 'date': '2013-11-22 13:25:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(5 inline comments)

Well, this piece of code is the most confusing part in your “Change conductor to cast to build_and_run_instance". [1]
Now it makes much more sense to me as a separate patch. :)
[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/43194/21

Please compare the exception handling logic in Havana release and this patch.
As you can see, in Havana, this logic is very clean. Each level above hides the detail of below levels. So that "BuildAbortException" is handled as a special case of "UnexpectedTaskStateError". While this patch reverses the logic, and using UnexpectedTaskStateError as a communicating method to let top level (do_build_and_run_instance) do the dirty job, which is very counter-intuitive.

So I'd suggest the logic in _build_resources should be reversed, and handle BuildAbortException as a special case of UnexpectedTaskStateError if identified as DELETING.
After reversing the logic, ".error" notification should be sent instead of ".end" for UnexpectedTaskStateError in _build_and_run_instance.

Havana Logic:
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
run_instance ->                      _run_instance ->                _build_instance
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
                                                                                       UnexpectedTaskStateError <-
                                                                                       (‘delete’)
                                             BuildAbortException <-
                                             (“.end” notification msg, NO re-raise)
BuildAbortException
(never caught here)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
                                                                                       UnexpectedTaskStateError <-
                                                                                       (other than ‘delete’)
                                             Exception<-
                                             (“.error” notification msg, set “error” state, and re-raise)

Current Logic:
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
do_build_and_run_instance -> _build_and_run_instance -> _build_resources
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
                                                                                       UnexpectedTaskStateError <-
                                                                                       (‘delete’)
                                             UnexpectedTaskStateError <-
                                             (“.end” notification msg, AND re-raise)
cleanup network <-
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
                                                                                       UnexpectedTaskStateError <-
                                                                                       (other than ‘delete’)
                                             BuildAbortException <-
                                             (“.end” notification msg, AND re-raise)
BuildAbortException <-
cleanup network and set “error" state <-'}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2013-11-22 15:57:04.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-22 16:34:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

Sorry, but it seems my comments has not been responded yet. Is this patch WIP?"}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2013-11-25 18:26:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Qiu Yu:  Sorry, I missed your earlier comments as I was focused on other tasks.  Patchset 2 was only pushed up as part of the dependency chain for the following patch, but it is a little bit WIP.

This can be cleaned up as there is now an UnexpectedDeletingTaskStateError so a special case of UnexpectedTaskStateError is no longer needed.  But I do disagree a bit on the usage of BuildAbortException, and part of that is how I chose to handle Exception.  

I wanted all expected conditions to be explicitly handled and not left up to a general Exception block.  So then I need to model the idea of an exception that fails the build and sets an ERROR state, and an exception that handles a delete which shouldn't set an error state.  The delete already causes an UnexpectedTaskState exception, now UnexpectedDeletedTaskState, so I decided to use BuildAbortException to mean the build should fail and ERROR.

I realize that it contradicts the usage in run_instance, so I'm willing to make a new exception that means fail the build and error.  But nothing about the definition of BuildAbortException in nova/exceptions.py seems to contradict my usage of it.  And I think it's ok to let UnexpectedTaskStateError, or UnexpectedDeletedTaskStateError, propagate up to the top.

I'm willing to discuss the idea of creating new exceptions to express the concepts I listed above.  But I think my logic is sound, though it uses the exceptions a little differently."}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2013-11-25 22:33:40.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-25 23:20:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

commit_message:
Better exception handling for deletes during build

To retain parity with the current run_instance boot process we should
not set the instance to ERROR if a delete occurs while it's building.

Some instance updates were moved into try/except blocks so the
task_state check failures are handled properly.  And a test for a
condition that can't occur was removed.

Part of bp remove-cast-to-schedule-run-instance

Change-Id: I688059404d6b697bd21f6037252dbe628c1b24f2

Does what it claims to. I tried it out on a container with an object in it, and it went into exponential backoff mode, then finished once I deleted the file.

The one thing that might be worth adding (in a follow-on patch, of course) is support for yielding some whitespace while in the middle of retrying. As it stands now, if you go with 8 retries, that's ~48s plus request time that can be spent in backoff mode without giving any bytes to the client.

To be fair, the whitespace yielding's not perfect now; if it's 2s to next scheduled yield and the next request takes 5s, then the yield happens late. With the new backoff, though, the inter-yield time can get arbitrarily large even if requests remain fast.

However, the default behavior is as it was before, and if a deployer keeps the delete_container_retry_count small, then it'll be an improvement over what exists now, so ship it!"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-01-07 22:26:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: No score

commit_message:
Adds a retry mechanism when deleting containers

Bulk middleware now has a mechanism to retry a delete when the
HTTP response code is 409. This happens when the container still
has objects. It can be useful in a bulk delete where you delete
all the objects in a container and then try to delete the container.
It is very likely that at the end it will fail because the replica
objects have not been deleted by the time the middleware got a
successful response.

Change-Id: I1614fcb5cc511be26a9dda90753dd08ec9546a3c
Closes-Bug: #1253478

commit_message:
Set include_service_catalog to False

include_service_catalog is a parameter in swift authtoken configuration.
Set to False improves performances.

Closes-Bug #1257738
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

Change-Id: Ie5dd2de45fce79e4da7ccb5b37d7c69ee1cb5198
(cherry picked from commit 2fc0354936bd89889f2e37f92e2a4acb501ca785)

"}, {'created': '2014-01-08 17:09:22.000000000', 'message': "Make nova preserve state in /mnt/state

commit_message:
Make nova preserve state in /mnt/state

This does not move config files, only nova's data files. We need this to
support separation of readonly root partition and a long living
preserved state partition.

Change-Id: I878e3cb57607ff72d8f1bf60a3828cf06a3feeb7

commit_message:
Create endpoint requires service_id

The spec didn't show that the service_id is required when
creating an endpoint.

Change-Id: I4a2838978b9a9a9486feeca5ec7ac5c37bd6a7d3

commit_message:
Tox fails to build environment because of MySQL-Python

The last version of MySQL-Python (>=1.2.4) needs the lib mysqlclient to
work. This patch adds a comment in the global-requirements to inform
Administrators. They have to install this library.

Change-Id: Iac1038f673efc035bca9ec703d6293c8cefae58c

commit_message:
Handle "inf" message in RAM limit chart

It captures byte value should be infinite to display a text message to
the user. The message displayed is the same as shown in the other
charts in the event that they also have infinite value.

Change-Id: I5686f3bdf7d0661b1761522fe376e289aff657ed
Closes-Bug: #1237350

commit_message:
Updates single flat use-case example for RHEL/CentOS/Fedora

Adds specific configuration options for RHEL, CentOS and Fedora
based distributions which were missing - e.g. the guide presumed
RabbitMQ was in use despite it not being relevant for these
platforms. In addition it adds clarity on where to find further
information or how to complete a specific step where necessary,
something the existing implementation lacked.

Now uses openstack-config in RHEL and SUSE based platforms.

Change-Id: I6c9a45114afbfa99ea2d01a3f682a0dc78a72530
backport: havana
Closes-Bug: 1266418

commit_message:
Consider  @,! in properties protection rule as a configuration error

In roles based property protection, if '@' and '!' are in the same rule then the
glance api will not start considering this an Invalid Configuration.

DocImpact
Closes-bug: #1260333
