commit_message:
neutron-rootwrap-xen-dom0 handles data from stdin

The neutron-rootwrap-xen-dom0 script and the netwrap plugin have been
modified to pass stdin from one to the other.

Change-Id: Ie97980873ed95f2c96eb68f8de611de1a733b130
Closes-Bug: #1259748

commit_message:
Enables db2 server disconnects to be handled pessimistically

A checkout listener can be added to sqlalchemy to be able to
handle database disconnect pessimistically and avoid an error in
the event of a DB restart or simply a temp connection issue due
to network glitches. At the moment only mysql is enabled with
this feature. This patch enables db2 as well.

Oslo version in change I5563360b43c4b648f5b035099b0e1d2e71d32503

Partial-Bug: #1231657
Change-Id: Icc032b2ebecf820a352c12330d6dd673c8655998

[{'created': '2013-12-18 13:28:17.000000000', 'message': 'Minor Python 3 fixes

 * basestring does not exist anymore in Python 2: use six.string_types instead
 * In "try: .../except Exception as err: ...", err is a local variable, it does
   no more exist after the except block. Copy the exception in a new cls_error
   variable to fix Python 3 support.
 * dict.iteritems() does not exist in Python 3, use dict.items() instead.
   Performances don't matter in a unit test.

Change-Id: I2efb14b3838f78d1ed5e09b3ccd4e796a3448aee

commit_message:
Minor Python 3 fixes

basestring does not exist anymore in Python 3: use six.string_types instead.

In "try: .../except Exception as err: ...", err is a local variable, it does no
more exist after the except block. Copy the exception in a new cls_error
variable to fix Python 3 support.

Extract of Python 3 documentation: "When an exception has been assigned using
as target, it is cleared at the end of the except clause. (...) Exceptions are
cleared because with the traceback attached to them, they form a reference
cycle with the stack frame, keeping all locals in that frame alive until the
next garbage collection occurs."

http://docs.python.org/3.3/reference/compound_stmts.html#try

Change-Id: I2efb14b3838f78d1ed5e09b3ccd4e796a3448aee

commit_message:
Fix exception deserialiation on Python 3

Builtin exceptions are now in the builtins module, the exceptions module has
been removed.

Fix also the unit test for tracebacks, Unicode representation doesn't start
with "u" prefix anymore (u'...').

Change-Id: I422be457e23066699950c9a3999878ecf65f1b3f

[{'created': '2013-12-31 16:08:00.000000000', 'message': "Modify default prefix for solidfire account

The SolidFire driver creates a unique account at volume
creation composed of <cinderhost-tenantID>.This is fine
until one tries to implement HA Cinder or moves their
Cinder node to another machine.

This patch changes the default setting to be an empty string
(ie no prefix), but still allows backward compatability by setting
the config option to 'hostname'.

DoccImpact: Changes default for account-prefix, for backwards compatability
use the non-default 'hostname'

Change-Id: I500ea14c1b4e9e3efd51c035cc3c4e6232da9dd6
Closes-Bug: 1265208

commit_message:
Modify default prefix for solidfire account

The SolidFire driver creates a unique account at volume
creation composed of <cinderhost-tenantID>.This is fine
until one tries to implement HA Cinder or moves their
Cinder node to another machine.

This patch changes the default setting to be an empty string
(ie no prefix), but still allows backward compatability by setting
the config option to 'hostname'.

DocImpact: Changes default for account-prefix, for backwards compatability
use the non-default 'hostname'

Change-Id: I500ea14c1b4e9e3efd51c035cc3c4e6232da9dd6
Closes-Bug: 1265208

Fix check_nvp_config erroneous complaint

Add the missing ingredient to the boolean test. This is
not a straight cherry-pick from a trunk fix, as the
utility tool has been renamed in Icehouse.

commit_message:
Remove unused variables in imagebackend.py

The method create() in /nova/virt/libvirt/ imagebackend.py has two unused
variable: old_format and features.These should be removed.

Change-Id: Id7b8661a162fbdf33de21b29892b5244ef301da7
Closes-Bug: #1266450

commit_message:
Remove #noqa from most common imports and add them to import_exceptions

We have a lot of import with #noqa that is there to ignore h302,
because it's traditional to import and use a name directly, instead
of a whole module. This hides other errors and gives people the
impression that it's actually fine to import non-modules, you just
have to slap #noqa on those lines.

I went through the code and identified about a dozen names that are
most commonly imported this way. I remove the #noqa tag from them,
and added them to the list in import_exceptions.

I also removed a few unused imports that were revealed in the process.

Change-Id: I27afb8e2b1d4759ec974ded9464d8f010312ee78

commit_message:
Get better format for long lines with PrettyTable

Based on current implement, the cli output format will be bad if
the lines are too long. This issue can be fixed by setting 'max_width'.
However, there is a bug against it, see
https://code.google.com/p/prettytable/source/browse/trunk/CHANGELOG?r=85
line 3. So the requirements.txt is updated as well.

docImpact
Fixes bug 1251283

Change-Id: I0d4192ad9d10a3d6d47a8319463a5edb57719a68

commit_message:
Add DB2 support to nova on redhat platform

Add three new attributes
default["openstack"]["compute"]["platform"]["mysql_python_packages"]
default["openstack"]["compute"]["platform"]["db2_python_packages"]
default["openstack"]["compute"]["platform"]["postgresql_python_packages"]
and add install DB python packages block in nova-common recipe

Change-Id: Ia862c821102119a784c4d8869418253e4ccdb137
Implements: blueprint db2-support

Add a new attribute

Implements: blueprint db2-support

commit_message:
Include 'role[os-image-upload]' to upload images

The os-image role is a roll-up role, so if any attributes for uploading images
are included, they'll get uploaded. Also included replacing double-quotes with
single quotes, per rubocop's complaints.

Change-Id: I38b53033dfb56ae8f8e1256cbb6c04208abb0b26

commit_message:
Remove lingering celery dependencies out of RPM dependencies.

There were two celery-related dependencies still lurking in the RPM
dependencies file after the move to oslo.messaging. This commit
removes the last of those.

Change-Id: I5f2c6851cc1d97f6c6defc408b622907a6fe0322

commit_message:
Add upgrade-horizon

Upgrade horizon along with the rest of devstack before running new
devstack tests and tempest.

upgrade-horizon is based off of upgrade-keystone.

Change-Id: I6a6e4da06806cb840d7af673673e06f34eb297e0
Related-Bug: #1265057

subject: Add support for specifying custom domains
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 4, 'name': 'Dolph Mathews', 'email': 'dolph.mathews@gmail.com', 'username': 'dolph'}, {'_account_id': 970, 'name': 'Dean Troyer', 'email': 'dtroyer@gmail.com', 'username': 'dtroyer'}, {'_account_id': 2218, 'name': 'Adam Young', 'email': 'adam@younglogic.com', 'username': 'ayoung'}, {'_account_id': 4162, 'name': 'Paul Belanger', 'email': 'pabelanger@redhat.com', 'username': 'pabelanger'}, {'_account_id': 6482, 'name': 'Steve Martinelli', 'email': 's.martinelli@gmail.com', 'username': 'stevemar'}, {'_account_id': 6506, 'name': 'Anastasia Guzikova', 'email': 'aguzikova@mirantis.com', 'username': 'aguzikova'}, {'_account_id': 7191, 'name': 'Jamie Lennox', 'email': 'jamielennox@gmail.com', 'username': 'jamielennox'}, {'_account_id': 7529, 'name': 'Bo Tang', 'email': 'botang.usa@gmail.com', 'username': 'townbull'}, {'_account_id': 7761, 'name': 'Jun Jie Nan', 'email': 'nanjunjie@gmail.com', 'username': 'nanjj'}, {'_account_id': 8996, 'name': 'Florent Flament', 'email': 'contact@florentflament.com', 'username': 'florent'}]

Build succeeded.

- gate-python-openstackclient-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/89/60989/1/check/gate-python-openstackclient-pep8/7898530 : SUCCESS in 1m 06s
- gate-python-openstackclient-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/89/60989/1/check/gate-python-openstackclient-docs/802ff9d/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 1m 06s

- gate-python-openstackclient-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/89/60989/1/check/gate-python-openstackclient-python27/866441a : SUCCESS in 1m 14s
- gate-python-openstackclient-python33 http://logs.openstack.org/89/60989/1/check/gate-python-openstackclient-python33/0f13ea1 : FAILURE in 25s (non-voting)
'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-12-10 14:53:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Quick question Paul, I've been wanting to eliminate the distinction between _NAME and _ID in the auth options.  We've already done that in the command options, is that a possibility here?"}, {'account_id': 4162, 'date': '2013-12-10 15:28:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Dean: Anything this possible! If that's what people want, I don't have an issue updating the patch.  Are you wanting ID or name?"}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-12-10 16:29:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'd like the user to see OS_DOMAIN and OS_USER_DOMAIN and be able to give either an ID or a name.

I'll do the same with OS_PROJECT soon"}, {'account_id': 4162, 'date': '2013-12-10 16:53:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

How are you determining if the value of OS_DOMAIN is an ID or name?'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-12-10 17:41:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I doubt find_resource() is going to work as that assume auth has already happened.  I also assume the v3 auth API requires one or the other and doesn't just try them both so I've planned to do that, try name first and if it fails try ID."}, {'account_id': 6482, 'date': '2013-12-13 02:27:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

You could also test to see if domain id is a uuid. But that might not work all the time, especially when using devstack, last time i checked it was actually a string. 

Also, could you change the first line of the commit message? I was a bit confused initially. Suggest "add domain support for identity client"?'}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2013-12-16 03:34:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I don't think it's a good idea to get rid of the id/name distinction. I can see why for aesthetics but we have this currently in the keystone v2 CLI and there is no way before time to distinguish between a name and ID as there is no guarantee that any ID is a UUID. 

The way we therefore have to do it is to send the request as an ID and if that doesn't work re-issue as a name. It's not a good scenario. How are you handling this already?"}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-12-16 22:10:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Jamie, I'm not handling it today the way I want...that why I'd like to change it now.  Does the Horizon interface have separate text boxes for domain name and ID?"}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2013-12-17 02:22:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Dean, I'm really not sure how horizon handles it but i think in general that the user cases are different.

I'm interested if you have a way to solve the "is it an id or name" problem, but in general i think a better solution is to just come up with a really clean rule for distinguishing them as people using the CLI will generally be able to handle the difference. 

Obviously this is not a keystone specific problem. 

Probably the plain 
    --user-{id,name}=XXX 
is best but you could get more creative 
    --user {id,name}:XXX

both get annoying with keystone when we start talking about user_domain_id'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-12-17 14:56:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

We can leave this as it is for now.  It does need tests for the new options and env vars.'}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2013-12-20 14:52:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

(5 inline comments)

+1 because this is a much needed step in the right direction, but it's actually incomplete and the help messages perhaps aren't specific enough... but those issues can be addressed in a subsequent patches if desired. comments inline!

This also appears to fix bug 1198171 (if I'm understanding the bug correctly)"}, {'account_id': 6506, 'date': '2013-12-24 11:25:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Dolph, Paul,

This patch can also fix bug 1198171, if we add project_domain_id/project_domain_name support.
Otherwise there will be this error still:
ERROR: cliff.app Could not find project, myproject. (HTTP 401)
and debug confirms a suggestion that 'myproject' is searched in 'default' domain in this case.
It works with this additional patch.

diff --git a/openstackclient/common/clientmanager.py b/openstackclient/common/clientmanager.py
index 4c8e023..79ebb65 100644
--- a/openstackclient/common/clientmanager.py
+++ b/openstackclient/common/clientmanager.py
@@ -46,6 +46,7 @@ class ClientManager(object):
                  project_id=None, username=None, password=None,
                  region_name=None, verify=True, api_version=None,
                  user_domain_name=None, user_domain_id=None, domain_id=None,
+                 project_domain_name=None, project_domain_id=None,
                  domain_name=None):
         self._token = token
         self._url = url
@@ -58,6 +59,8 @@ class ClientManager(object):
         self._password = password
         self._user_domain_id = user_domain_id
         self._user_domain_name = user_domain_name
+        self._project_domain_id = project_domain_id
+        self._project_domain_name = project_domain_name
         self._region_name = region_name
         self._api_version = api_version
         self._service_catalog = None
diff --git a/openstackclient/identity/client.py b/openstackclient/identity/client.py
index a612874..b19388c 100644
--- a/openstackclient/identity/client.py
+++ b/openstackclient/identity/client.py
@@ -48,6 +48,8 @@ def make_client(instance):
             password=instance._password,
             user_domain_id=instance._user_domain_id,
             user_domain_name=instance._user_domain_name,
+            project_domain_id=instance._project_domain_id,
+            project_domain_name=instance._project_domain_name,
             domain_id=instance._domain_id,
             domain_name=instance._domain_name,
             tenant_name=instance._project_name,
diff --git a/openstackclient/shell.py b/openstackclient/shell.py
index d2ce7aa..974a822 100644
--- a/openstackclient/shell.py

             default=utils.env('OS_USER_DOMAIN_ID'),
             help='Authentication user domain id (Env: OS_USER_DOMAIN_ID)')
         parser.add_argument(
+            '--os-project-domain-name',
+            metavar='<auth-project-domain-name>',
+            default=utils.env('OS_PROJECT_DOMAIN_NAME'),
+            help='Authentication project domain name '

+        parser.add_argument(

+            default=utils.env('OS_PROJECT_DOMAIN_ID'),
+            help='Authentication project domain id (Env: OS_PROJECT_DOMAIN_ID)'
+        )
+        parser.add_argument(
             '--os-region-name',
             metavar='<auth-region-name>',
             default=env('OS_REGION_NAME'),
@@ -329,6 +341,8 @@ class OpenStackShell(app.App):
             project_id=self.options.os_project_id,
             user_domain_id=self.options.os_user_domain_id,
             user_domain_name=self.options.os_user_domain_name,
+            project_domain_id=self.options.os_project_domain_id,
+            project_domain_name=self.options.os_project_domain_name,
             username=self.options.os_username,
             password=self.options.os_password,

commit_message:
Add support for specifying custom domains

Add the ability to pass user_domain_id / user_domain_name, domain_id
/ domain_name, and project_domain_id / project_domain_name to keystone.
These parameters are the first step needed to getting multi-domain
support working via the CLI.

Closes-Bug: #1198171
Change-Id: I81a8534913978ff1cce01ec02741ae477e8c5fa4
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <paul.belanger@polybeacon.com>
Signed-off-by: Bo Tang <btang@cs.utsa.edu>

commit_message:
Map HTTP request codes in jsonschema

Added schema.py to queues/api/v1/jsonschema. This file maps out the HTTP
request codes in jsonschema to be used by the API.

Partially-Implements: cross-transport-api-spec

Change-Id: I4da61c13a39c0bfe2873f65d14647315494b3554

commit_message:
Allow passing in a handler

A handler is typically used to use alternate
providers of async functionality in kazoo, for
eventlet a specialized handler can be provided,
or the same for gevent; so it's nice to allow
the user to pass that in (the default if not
passed in will be a SequentialThreadingHandler
which as we know in python means threads, and
threads aren't such great performers due to
the GIL).

Change-Id: Iad928c26c6eeda1e735ae8e1b1f8124d0e45404f

commit_message:
WIP: Add APIs for managing TLDs

This change adds APIs for managing TLDs.  Previously TLDs were in
2 files.  With this change, the TLDs will be in the central's storage
database.

commit_message:
Fixed usage of strutils.safe_encode due to py3

safe_encode method from strutils returns different classtype for
py27(str) and py33(bytes) due to different types of string and text.

Related to blueprint make-python3-compatible

Change-Id: I3b4d75702d6cede3a7c074138a70416581707944

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-01-08 13:58:32.000000000', 'message': 'Add option to swiftclient to download only changed files

swift has already the upload option "--changed" to upload only changed files.
This patch adds the same feature to the download option. If used the MD5
hexdigest of each file is compared to the etag value and unchanged files are
simply skipped.

Change-Id: I8cdd726c3cad08ecbe17189e673d25ecb64327df
'}]
commit_message:
Add option to swiftclient to download only changed files

swift has already the upload option "--changed" to upload only changed files.
This patch adds the same feature to the download option. If used the MD5
hexdigest of each file is compared to the etag value and unchanged files are
simply skipped.

Change-Id: I8cdd726c3cad08ecbe17189e673d25ecb64327df

commit_message:
libvirt: clean in libvirt/*.py

 + The attribute snapshot was not defined (W0201).
 + The private method _text_node should be used as function (R0201).
 + Replaces staticmethod calls by classname instead of instance ref.
 + Removes duplicate code in volume.py for the method: get_hash_str.
 + Fixes a test in libvirt to be more coherent with the static
   method _direct_io_stub.

Change-Id: Ie61350dc0c017feff6b85958c7b3c65da501bfd2

commit_message:
Remove unneeded /var/run/nova/keys from install

At one point /var/run/nova/keys may have been needed but I cannot find
it referenced anywhere else.

This dir won't have any impact on a running system anyway since /var/run
will be a tmpfs mount created a boot.

Change-Id: I550cccb0fb876ef23475014c869789d0a4da6bbe

*Find()*. Comments are also updated.

commit_message:
Fixing misspelled encryption key in QemuImgInfo

This modification addresses Bug #1257829, specifically addresing
the use of a misspelled 'encryption' key to retrieve image encryption
information returned by calls to the 'qemu-img' command. Updates made
to oslo-incubator in the following patch are included, along with test
cases:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/61877/

Change-Id: I6df2dc6b1569c1c1f2d2db1e92c650ef13c15274
Closes-Bug: #1257829

commit_message:
Adds new options on libvirt drivers

 * console; choice of the console for message output.
 * max_console_bytes; the maximum number of bytes
   retrieved from the console

Note: In relation with the bug #1259323
      but does not correct it.

DocImpact
Change-Id: Ibac2b48908f48e42d827968d38fe28cb6df0dd51

commit_message:
Utilizes assertIsNone and assertIsNotNone

Using assertEqual/assertNotEqual to test if an element
is or is not None is too python2.4.
Our unit testing framework supports assertIsNone and assertIsNotNone
which were created for these types of tests.

Change-Id: I969ee943e31b4fa0291f6cb9e21e2f654e88e66e

"}]
commit_message:
Update spec_helper to include 'chefspec/berkshelf'

This minor change allows you to run rspec outside of strainer while
still having cookbook dependencies automatically handled by berkshelf
(which also means you can run individual chefspec tests).

Note that this change does marginally increase the time it takes to run
a strainer test.

A similar change was recently accepted in the openstack-compute
cookbook.

Change-Id: Ia5b5f3cc8aab853dd0e8c3b120ed178b0f0887db

commit_message:
Reuse common functional from cliutils

Module novaclient.utils has the same methods like in cliutils
from Oslo. In the process of unification of the clients code
we should reuse common functionality from Oslo.

 + Removes methods: arg, env, add_arg, unauthenticated,
   isunauthenticated
 + Using new methods from cliutils: arg, env, add_arg, isunauthenticated
 + Correctly indenting the code

Related to blueprint common-client-library-2
Change-Id: Iade2f2b1af14c14c737b4188883e0170a36b0578

commit_message:
Use Resource class from Oslo

All methods of Resource class from keystoneclient are similar to methods
from common code.
In the process of unification of the clients code we should
reuse common functionality from Oslo.

I like the idea behind this patch, however, I think we should structure this a bit better. For example:

  1. We should have a versioned schema.py module (under v1, v2, etc packages)
  2. I'd like to see more cases being tested (or all of them?)
  3. I think we can make this a bit more generic. For example, A function that takes a response and an operation in and tests the response schema and headers (?)."}, {'account_id': 7498, 'date': '2013-12-11 18:31:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Thanks Flavio for the feedback.

1. We should have a versioned schema.py module (under v1, v2, etc packages) -Good Point! What abt moving schema.py to marconi/queues/api/v1/response ? This will keep the request (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/59508/) & response schemas in the same directory.
  2. I'd like to see more cases being tested (or all of them?) - My plan is to have similar validation for all our API reponses. But this will have to be in a future patchset due to other priorities (tempest)
  3. I think we can make this a bit more generic. For example, A function that takes a response and an operation in and tests the response schema and headers (?). - I think we already do this, unless I misunderstand 
As is base.py.assertSchema() takes in the response & expected schema, and does the generic response validation. Functional tests already do some header validation. eg. https://github.com/openstack/marconi/blob/master/tests/functional/wsgi/v1/test_messages.py#L56"}, {'account_id': 6971, 'date': '2013-12-17 17:01:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-17 17:04:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Doesn't seem to work

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-04 12:15:24.000000000', 'message': "Removes unnecessary api-paste.ini configuration

Paremeter api_paste_config defaults to '/etc/nova/api-paste.ini',
so it is not needed to set it in nova.conf. Without having
the parameter in nova.conf we can use this module together
with dist.conf. Also filter:authtoken parameters should be
in nova.conf and not in api-paste.ini. Removes filter:authtoken

commit_message:
Removes unnecessary api-paste.ini configuration

Paremeter api_paste_config defaults to '/etc/nova/api-paste.ini',
so it is not needed to set it in nova.conf. Without having
the parameter in nova.conf we can use this module together
with dist.conf. Also filter:authtoken parameters should be
in nova.conf and not in api-paste.ini. Removes filter:authtoken
configuration from api-paste.ini in case it is filled there.

Change-Id: Ice3883bc72fe303cbaf32a3fc46fb9da302b1a3b
(cherry picked from commit ee469886921b7168a0ae974f7557d355af98aacb)

commit_message:
Introduce keystone_url parameter

This parameter deprecates keystone_host, keystone_port & keystone_scheme
and allows to pass a complete url.

Implements blueprint serve-keystone-from-wsgi

Change-Id: Ia8aa6e6377abf0e84427174fb946f4efa5defa12
(cherry picked from commit 314df2136eb54ac95d0716d00f20265c5c439494)

commit_message:
horizon replaced nodejs by a python alternative

since commit a0739c9423a4c559b45af96fa4cdb30539dcdbd7 and the Havana
release, horizon uses a pure Python alternative to nodejs.

Horizon changed the way to use the compress utility, the option
offline_compress is no longer available.
Thanks to Maxime Vidori for the information.

Change-Id: Ie290701b00c97352838e13182b940a6de46a591f
(cherry picked from commit fae0d04b82867dab3c355e5f1d5a9b2d0054f949)

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-01-07 16:47:02.000000000', 'message': 'Fix filter name for puppetdb

When creating the filter class name the last part is not capitalized.
So Swift::Storage::Filter::Healthcheck[bla] is named
Swift::Storage::Filter::healthcheck[bla].  Puppet don't detect the
syntax error as the resource is "created" within a string.  But
puppetdb's parser do not let this work.

This fix it and adjust the tests.

Change-Id: If11c3ad0e98d14b9387b3daa4afeb118387100f8
Closes-Bug: #1252998
(cherry picked from commit 3566f9fa651d8e50a81a3bcb042beb126da46f3d)
'}]
commit_message:
Fix filter name for puppetdb

When creating the filter class name the last part is not capitalized.
So Swift::Storage::Filter::Healthcheck[bla] is named
Swift::Storage::Filter::healthcheck[bla].  Puppet don't detect the
syntax error as the resource is "created" within a string.  But
puppetdb's parser do not let this work.

This fix it and adjust the tests.

Change-Id: If11c3ad0e98d14b9387b3daa4afeb118387100f8
Closes-Bug: #1252998
(cherry picked from commit 3566f9fa651d8e50a81a3bcb042beb126da46f3d)

'}, {'account_id': 7822, 'date': '2013-12-30 19:52:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

This is a nice feature to have. I'm surprised it took this long to have an option for it. Can you cherry pick this back?"}, {'account_id': 7155, 'date': '2013-12-31 11:49:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

(1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2014-01-02 12:36:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Sebastien: I just copy / paste from original commit: https://review.openstack.org/gitweb?p=openstack%2Fnova.git;a=commitdiff;h=c21cbe8cd59bffe9b3d1fe9d9f4a8dc3da8cf313'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2014-01-02 16:05:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

This seems fine but why not just use nova_config for this? (and keep our modules simpler)

If we had a reason to change the nova default behaviour I suppose I might buy this approach. Otherwise just using nova_config seems reasonable enough right?'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2014-01-02 16:05:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

"}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2014-01-02 19:58:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I may be wrong at all, but this is why I like to add new flags:
*avoid the use of nova_config when you build manifest and just care of declaring class with good params.
*let users know what they should care when deploying OpenStack. Example with this flag, in nova::compute which means the user will understand this flag is for compute nodes only.

In my opinion, this kind of patch helps people to deploy OpenStack without strong knowledges in specific OpenStack projects.

Again, I may be wrong, and if you prefer I can abandon this patch. From my side, it has been some time I use to deploy OpenStack, and most of what I learnt comes from puppet modules which help to understand the way to configure OpenStack.'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2014-01-03 14:32:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Emilien: Nova has so many options (over 500) so we have to draw the line somewhere lest our puppet modules become unwieldy.

This flag doesn't fall in the critical path for installing Nova compute nodes so my preference would be to use nova_config to manage this one..."}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2014-01-03 15:55:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Dan: Thank you for your feedback. So what's the policy now? No more flags that could be configured by nova_config?"}, {'account_id': 7156, 'date': '2014-01-08 01:44:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I tend to agree with Dan on this one. I feel modules are getting bloated with a handful of parameters being added recently.

Although we can argue that all configs are useful to some extend, lets face it: end users can't use our manifests without a composition layer of some sort. I therefore expect those people to be able to add those configs to their composition layer. It's not like they CAN'T configure resume_guests_state_on_host_boot without our help/support. Let's not (re)create puppet-openstack where it tries to support all use cases and accommodate everyone's needs."}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2014-01-08 08:29:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

Thank you Dan & Mathieu for your great feedback, and it makes sense at all to abandon this one.'}]

will convert ":" and "-" to "_". It should not be so.

Change-Id: I9d09dd101eb1df88ca0bc7487c810eb55b836b89
Closes-bug: #1241218

commit_message:
Utilizes assertIsNone and assertIsNotNone

Using assertEqual/assertNotEqual to test if an element
is or is not None is too python2.4.
Our unit testing framework supports assertIsNone and assertIsNotNone
which were created for these types of tests.

Change-Id: Ieba2d4ce5602885dc8a33a938a40f3086879b2c3

Fixes bug 1262335

Previously, the first and last sample timestamps associated
with a resource were calculated by the storage driver, but
then discarded.

Now, we include these values in the API resource representation.

Change-Id: I3cf6081e1ac1294083f6326f85dabebab0d02203
'}]
commit_message:
1st & last sample timestamps in Resource representation

Fixes bug 1262335

Previously, the first and last sample timestamps associated
with a resource were calculated by the storage driver, but
then discarded.

Now, we include these values in the API resource representation.

Change-Id: I3cf6081e1ac1294083f6326f85dabebab0d02203

commit_message:
Wait for the server before validate the rotation result

This commit is for test:
tempest.api.compute.servers.test_server_actions:\
ServerActionsTestJSON.test_create_backup
In most cases, the nova service sends the response of
the request that queries the backups before the rotation
function completes its work, and then 3 backups will be
and the test will fail.
This commit makes the use case wait for the server to
become active before sends the query request to ensure
rotation task has completed before the verification.

Closes-Bug: #1257614

Change-Id: Ic6443e3835fdb9d53f5ab643a04312c59ecb4c58

commit_message:
Fix downgrade in 002_quota_class.py for MySQL

Downgrade in the script 002_quota_class.py is failing for MySQL
because there is an attempt to delete the quota_classes table
while the reservations table still has a foreign key defined.
The foreign key causes the delete of the quota_classes table to fail.

This change is based upon commit 8328fc46d783f4ec9286eededafa91afae89cba0
which makes a similar change to 018_add_qos_specs.py .

Change-Id: I81844a2da4fb3b831f1f9dead3634e82f54e559e
Closes-bug: 1265944

commit_message:
Fix the invalid argument of webob.exc.HTTPBadRequest

webob.exc.HTTPBadRequest() does not have a parameter 'reason'.

Change-Id: I65103ce72849e921150c4d098993fa523f53fe3a
Closes-Bug: #1264223

commit_message:
Removed deprecated config option hp3par_domain

The hp3par_domain config option was deprecated in the Havana release.
This just removes it from the code, test and config sample file
for the Icehouse release.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ib3820cfc1b0db8a8b5755ac59d30691ce832fcea

I don't think we need to keep a copy. I think we can just import relevant bits."}, {'account_id': 668, 'date': '2013-12-26 20:12:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

This is a very big patch that pulls in over 23,000 lines of code, and introduces a fork. If we take this approach, let's do it in a lightweight way that only replicates the minimum needed to use the CLI, and not everything for using all of OpenStack, since nobody will use this client for that purpose. Can we prune this patch down to a few hundred lines of code? If not, can we make the Solum code a module that plugs into the OpenStack client? Perhaps we can script the installation of the base client, and then plug our code into that."}, {'account_id': 9094, 'date': '2013-12-31 16:07:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I talked to Mordred and it sounds like he generally agrees with the plugin implementation you created; good work trailblazing through this.

However, we shouldn't copy the whole project to a Solum related project.  We should contribute directly to the OSC project instead to enable a Solum CLI from IRC discussion.  I realize this was probably done as a convenience to everyone however to make sure all of the code is in one place for people to test out the Assembly code."}, {'account_id': 9094, 'date': '2013-12-31 16:25:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
WIP: CLI code based on python-openstackclient

Added code for 'assembly show' command

For CLI processing we intend to use python-openstackclient.
Since Solum is not yet OS project, we cannot add solum specific
processing in the main python-openstackclient repository.
So we have decided to keep a local copy of it here.
We provide a script which can be used to sync the local copy
with the main repo.

blueprint solum-minimal-cli

commit_message:
Adjust import order according to PEP8 imports rule

This patch just adjust import order to follow PEP8 imports rule.
https://github.com/openstack-dev/hacking/blob/master/doc/source/index.rst#imports

Imports should be grouped in the following order:
1) Standard library imports
2) Related third party imports
3) Local application/library specific imports

Change-Id: Ib67dcbcf8f2ea02d8bb828602eeb0466330e8039

Log two Exceptions seperately when get images information

When get images information, two exceptions(NotFound and
Forbidden) not logged, I add log to the two exceptions.

Closes-Bug:#1263871

#auth_protocol

#signing_dir

#auth_version

commit_message:
Sync config generator from oslo-incubator

Sync from oslo-incubator with the following patches about the config
generator:

7c18261 Temporary workaround for config generator
4b3e32b Sort the output of config/generator.py by group name
806272e Improve error reporting on import failures
6cd1c33 Clean up extra modules code
3d077a3 Print the deprecated group/name for each option
aec6d94 config.generator: allow extra modules importing
ddc4f0d Fix error when no custom config file matches *.conf.sample
d4bf84d Allow generate_sample MODULEPATH to be set in env

UpgradeImpact

DocImpact, the default values in keystone_authtoken config group are
changed.

Change-Id: If7181e14db2e43e42255bb6221d0543c13c4e5a6

commit_message:
Avoid false negatives on message signature comparison

Fixes bug 1262255

Previously, samples for the 'instance.scheduled' meter were always
rejected with a false negative on the message signature verification.

The problem occured because certain resource metadata (such as the
block_device_mapping) in the 'scheduler.run_instance.scheduled'
notification are realized as a list of dict, and are thus similarly
encoded in the corresponding sample payload.

However the message signature computation then became indeterminate,
as the unicode representation of equivalent dicts is not guaranteed
equal (e.g. depends on insertion order in the case of hash collisions).

Now, we avoid false negatives by explicitly re-ordering insertion
into such dicts.

Change-Id: I77f7d89229518cf040608d7eb3307e2257bce07a

commit_message:
Add namespace cleanup options

Adds a configuration option to tell the network agents to delete
namespaces when they are no longer in use. The option defaults to
False so that the agent will not attempt to delete namespaces in
environments where this is not safe.

It affects only L3 & DHCP agents for now.

Change-Id: Ie9e27ae55b796ec12601dbfbeda45184188864f5
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

commit_message:
Whitelist external netaddr requirement

* tox.ini(testenv.install_command): Use the --allow-external and
--allow-insecure options so that pip 1.5 and later will assent to
retrieve the netaddr package even though it's not hosted on PyPI.
The --allow-insecure option is aliased to a clearer
--allow-unverified wording in 1.5, but the old form is being used to
avoid breaking users of 1.4.x and will be valid at least through
1.6.x according to comments in the pip source.

Change-Id: I005e752c8cb9bca78b1ebe777eb5230e9bf05bd8

commit_message:
Whitelist external netaddr requirement

* tox.ini(testenv.install_command): Use the --allow-external and
--allow-insecure options so that pip 1.5 and later will assent to
retrieve the netaddr package even though it's not hosted on PyPI.
The --allow-insecure option is aliased to a clearer
--allow-unverified wording in 1.5, but the old form is being used to
avoid breaking users of 1.4.x and will be valid at least through
1.6.x according to comments in the pip source.

Change-Id: I005e752c8cb9bca78b1ebe777eb5230e9bf05bd8

[{'created': '2013-12-18 14:29:29.000000000', 'message': "Filter out deleted images from storage usage

All database API's currently include deleted images in the calc of
storage usage. This is not an issue when deleted images don't have
locations. However, there are cases where a deleted image has deleted
locations as well and that causes the current algorithm to count those
locations as if they were allocating space.

Besides this bug, it makes sense to not load deleted images from the
database if we're actually not considering them as valid images.

Change-Id: I82f08a8f522c81541e4f77597c2ba0aeb68556ce
Closes-Bug: #1261738

"}, {'created': '2013-12-19 16:07:11.000000000', 'message': "Filter out deleted images from storage usage

All database API's currently include deleted images in the calc of
storage usage. This is not an issue when deleted images don't have
locations. However, there are cases where a deleted image has deleted
locations as well and that causes the current algorithm to count those
locations as if they were allocating space.

Besides this bug, it makes sense to not load deleted / killed /
pending-deleted images from the database if we're actually not
considering them as valid images.

The patch also filters out deleted locations.

NOTE: In the case of locations, it was not possible to add a test for
the deleted locations because it requires some changes that are not
worth in this patch. In order to mark a location as deleted, it's
necessary to go through the API and use a PATCH operation. Since this is
a database test, it doesn't make much sense to add API calls to it.

remove all the locations which won't help testing that specific case.

commit_message:
Filter out deleted images from storage usage

All database API's currently include deleted images in the calc of
storage usage. This is not an issue when deleted images don't have
locations. However, there are cases where a deleted image has deleted
locations as well and that causes the current algorithm to count those
locations as if they were allocating space.

Besides this bug, it makes sense to not load deleted / killed /
pending_delete images from the database if we're actually not
considering them as valid images.

The patch also filters out deleted locations.

NOTE: In the case of locations, it was not possible to add a test for
the deleted locations because it requires some changes that are not
worth in this patch. In order to mark a location as deleted, it's
necessary to go through the API and use a PATCH operation. Since this is
a database test, it doesn't make much sense to add API calls to it.
Calling the image_destroy function with an empty location list will
remove all the locations which won't help testing that specific case.

I'll work on a better solution for that in a follow-up patch.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I82f08a8f522c81541e4f77597c2ba0aeb68556ce
Closes-Bug: #1261738

commit_message:
Handle the metrics sent by nova notifier

Nova compute node can now get metrics from monitors and send
notifications to message bus. So, add listeners to handle the
metrics in ceilometer. This patch changes the directory layout
for compute notifications, because there will be other metrics
(e.g. network and cache Qos) to be added. The deployer can also
add the metrics they want. It's better to make a classification
of these metrics.

Nova blueprint utilization-aware-scheduling

Change-Id: I6f54ef18035c437370360bbaff6d71666d0323fe

commit_message:
Allow the Message class to have non-English default locales

This patch does an initial translation of the msgid (which is in
English) when the Message class is created, just in case the system's
default locale is not English.

commit_message:
Implementation of translation log handler

This patch implements the TranslationHandler which is a LogHandler that
enables translation of the log records before they are logged.

The handler is configured declaratively in the logging.conf as follows:

        [handlers]
        keys = translatedlog, translator

        [handler_translatedlog]
        class = handlers.WatchedFileHandler
        args = ('/var/log/api-localized.log',)
        formatter = context

        [handler_translator]
        class = openstack.common.log.TranslationHandler
        target = translatedlog
        args = ('zh_CN',)

A prototype version included with the initial version of the Message
class is removed.

Change-Id: I77b6b8a6f5b6360a9bb67ec56cdc927fe91597be

commit_message:
Add H904: don't wrap lines using a backslash

Hacking originally had a soft preference for () versus \ based line
continuation, but this has lead to unnecessary review churn. So in order
to reduce churn be stricter and don't allow \ based line continuation.

Related ML thread
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-November/019024.html

Change-Id: I010623344bc2c4bf86051f86a96afb3611c90342

commit_message:
Fix filter() usage due to python 3 compability

Built-in method filter() returns a list in Python 2.x [1], but it
returns an iterator in Python 3.x [2]. To remove the difference (and
make code more readable, also), we use list comprehension instead of filer().

[1] http://docs.python.org/2/library/functions.html#filter
[2] http://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#filter

Related to blueprint make-python3-compatible

Change-Id: Ifd42403309ba3a44693e0c7c856a64b861eca3e9

The database connection string was not marked as secret, so it
would be printed out in cleartext in the logs when config settings
were logged.

The database connection string typically contains the password
that's used to connect to the database, so it should be marked as

commit_message:
Fix database connection string is secret

The database connection string was not marked as secret, so it
would be printed out in cleartext in the logs when config settings
were logged.

The database connection string typically contains the password
that's used to connect to the database, so it should be marked as
secret so that it doesn't get logged.

Change-Id: If6e1026814262c961a4f22d90f546cec34831bc8

commit_message:
Middlelware to ensure request ID

The feature of the proposed middleware is simple:
* Generate request-id for each REST request
* Set the generated request-id to request environment
* Add X-OpenStack-Request-Id header to API response to return request-id

blueprint middleware-request-id

Note that to use this middleware with Context, we need to change
auth middlware so that request-id will be retreived from request env.

Change-Id: Ic7967cd62e7b743343d70f751b9238339171e013

commit_message:
Allow configurable ProcessLauncher liveness check

The current interval between ProcessLauncher checks of whether
a child process has exited - 0.01s - prioritizes fast respawning of
children at the expense of cpu usage.  This tradeoff may not be
appropriate for all clients of the class, so this patch makes the
interval configurable.  The current interval remains the default
to avoid changing expected behavior.

This patch was motivated by unnecessary idle cpu usage of the
Neutron service when configured to use ProcessLauncher-managed
worker processes.

Partial-Bug: #1095346

Change-Id: I2f5e06f98be1f75c21e6681967b573f5d88a4ed6

commit_message:
Readded section for Floating IP creation in admin guide

A user reported a missing section in the Havana admin guide for
creating and attaching floating IP addresses. As many users still
use nova-network I thought this should be put back in. I've added
a note to point towards the basic neutron equivalent. For the Icehouse
manual we should add more detail to support the floating IP concepts in
Neutron. Will revisit.

Change-Id: Iaa4387461a6f4775acf1f86dfde7b8afe226495f
Closes-Bug: #1263203

commit_message:
Extract keyring into more general cache

Keyring may not be the only auth caching mechanism we want to use.
Extract it from the base keystoneclient into a more generalized caching
class.

commit_message:
Delete control_exchange flag

control_exchange is duplicated in init.pp and ceilometer.pp which could
create duplicate declaration when declaring cinder and
cinder::ceilometer on same node.

Closes-bug #1266259
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

Change-Id: Ic1c5c880c421f43d2a125b2b5b58630fc55bc9c8

commit_message:
Code cleanup: use oslo's to_slug() instead of slugify()

The bash completion code is the sole user of the slugify() function
in utils, which is substantially similar to to_slug() provided in
strutils from oslo.

Change-Id: Ib4eb7e4c0fa0e9bc5c4a0856f6391911d8f8fd3b
Closes-bug: #1266118

commit_message:
Fix auth_token configuration.

- cache=swift.cache need to be in auth_token configuration not in
  keystoneauth.
- Make auth_token using the same facility for logging than main swift.

Closes-Bug: #1254487

Change-Id: If5a09da4d18f247dc42b99e6f666bc2867d06dcb
(cherry picked from commit 000d63b65417b9cf73763e1d25eef1a8f3b695a7)

- container_quotas

commit_message:
Don't create Member role

Creating the "_member_" role and "Member" role creates confusion.
"_member_" has special significance to keystone, so we keep that.

Horizon is modified to use "_member_" as the default role in [1].
This change should be merged after that.

See also rhbz#984294 [2]

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/60462/
[2] https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=984294

Change-Id: If4ed1c2c72ca67acad7b70651e68ff7ce68157dd
(cherry picked from commit 1dd4297243d6ce25115828d87302a72e9d3e1f72)

commit_message:
Add a note about restrictive firewall on rhel

RHEL/Centos/SL has a restrictive firewall by default, which
if left in an unaltered state prevents compute nodes from
talking to the controller (and therefore and unsuccessful
installation)

Since changing this is very basic sysadmin practice, just add
a small warning.

Change-Id: I5d564f612aaa6e7b14892bef79538dd3e387bfc9
Closes-Bug: 1241981

commit_message:
Add LVM module to OpenStack Common

This patch adds a simple LVM wrapper/interface to the
OpenStack-Common modules.  Currently we use LVM in a couple
of places, this would allow us to remove the duplication of
that code, particularly between Nova and Cinder as well as
up and coming projects like Manilla.

Implements Blueprint: add-lvm-module

Change-Id: I58dd70937110e50b5b5c49232e66f1c7ea82cbe6

commit_message:
Adds openstack-config options for Red Hat and SUSE distros

Documentation for configuring networking on dedicated network
node expected manual configuration file changes. Red Hat and SUSE
based platforms support openstack-config. These changes need to
be replicated for dedicated-network and compute host where appropriate.

Change-Id: I7cc23370fad0c441b1f8fcf8a7781c58b17fbd59
Closes-Bug: 1266409

commit_message:
Add domain_id to /v3 group responses

The example responses for the identity /v3 group responses
(create, get, and update group) didn't include the domain_id like
the real response does.

commit_message:
Fix path to auth token resource

The path for the token resource was /v3/tokens, but the identity
v3 spec says the path is /v3/auth/tokens.

For example, to get a token, you POST /v3/auth/tokens, not
POST /v3/tokens.

Change-Id: I4a7c8f3e23f81bef6ee50d30f834c23775c13561

Fix PATCH endpoint

The docs for PATCH endpoint said that there was no request body.
A request body is required which contains the fields to update.

Also, the response didn't show that the "endpoint" container was
included.

commit_message:
Install link to mysql unix socket

Default mysql socket for Fedora/RHEL mysql client lib is
/var/lib/mysql/mysql.sock.  Although we change this path in a mysql
config file, it's not sufficient because some clients don't read any
mysql config and just use default socket path.

For Fedora/RHEL this patch installs a link at the origional path.

Change-Id: Id46961278c9d33d04d555f14d8334c5fe2cb23c7

--allow-insecure options so that pip 1.5 and later will assent to
retrieve the netaddr package even though it's not hosted on PyPI.
The --allow-insecure option is aliased to a clearer
--allow-unverified wording in 1.5, but the old form is being used to
avoid breaking users of 1.4.x and will be valid at least through

Closes-Bug: #1266513

"}]
commit_message:
Whitelist external netaddr requirement

* tox.ini(testenv.install_command): Use the --allow-external and
--allow-insecure options so that pip 1.5 and later will assent to
retrieve the netaddr package even though it's not hosted on PyPI.
The --allow-insecure option is aliased to a clearer
--allow-unverified wording in 1.5, but the old form is being used to
avoid breaking users of 1.4.x and will be valid at least through
1.6.x according to comments in the pip source.

Change-Id: I7c29467ebdddee7a6c68ec3fd13579e4f0c40d30
Closes-Bug: #1266513
Co-Authored-By: Jeremy Stanley

class_name parameter is not used in both Nova v1.1/v3 API.
Nova considers the part of url as class_name.
For example, bar is considered as class_name in the following case:
 curl -i 'http://localhost:8774/v3/os-quota-class-sets/bar' -X PUT ..

This patch removes this unused paramter from quota_class.

"}]
commit_message:
Remove class_name parameter from quota_class

class_name parameter is not used in both Nova v1.1/v3 API.
Nova considers the part of url as class_name.
For example, bar is considered as class_name in the following case:
 curl -i 'http://localhost:8774/v3/os-quota-class-sets/bar' -X PUT ..

This patch removes this unused paramter from quota_class.

Change-Id: Id4eba5b2a17506bc04ea23ef1097ef9cdb9caf8a

commit_message:
Add a Message resource and a MessageIterator

This patch defines the Message resource and the MessageIterator. The
former represents a message unit and the possible operations that can be
executed from that resource. The later allows users to iterate over
Messages' pages and consume all available messages.

The patch also renames queue_id to queue._name which is more consistent
with the API terminology.

NOTE: Functional tests are missing and will be added in a separate
patch.

Change-Id: I8c871e326bd580964f15d4ffc16c6264f9825ba7
Partially-Implements: python-marconiclient-v1

commit_message:
Adding 2 rubocop configuration files

Keeping in accordance with the other projects, adding a few standard
settings for rubocop. Dont check line lengths, dont check for UTF-8
comments and dont suggest word arrays for attributes files.

Change-Id: I62a04e7a34f9cd9020caa1dff96b6fa38db807cd

commit_message:
Add Storage Policy Support to ssync

This patch makes ssync policy aware and adds plumbing required
for existing test cases to pass. It depends highly on the Replicator
patch for Storage Polcies (pending).

More unit tests will be added to cover multiple policies following
initial review/feedback on the functional code changes.

Change-Id: I10b59f94eb25bc344c654aec897b96c1e8c9f550
Implements: blueprint storage-policies

[{'created': '2014-01-07 15:18:21.000000000', 'message': 'Refactor keystone_user_role to be lazier

Currently, the entire list of user roles are
cached ASAP. Trying to pre-determine these
is very slow b/c there is no user role list
command in keystone, so you must iterate through
all tenant/user combinations to retrieve the list.

This patch makes the retrieval of all state info
lazy.

Partial-Bug: 1224179
Change-Id: I80a85f3ddf2c41fe447df5682ad31ac4df8f8b59
(cherry picked from commit a0a359801e7248b24d15b3acef3b398d5a2fb65f)
'}]
commit_message:
Refactor keystone_user_role to be lazier

Currently, the entire list of user roles are
cached ASAP. Trying to pre-determine these
is very slow b/c there is no user role list
command in keystone, so you must iterate through
all tenant/user combinations to retrieve the list.

This patch makes the retrieval of all state info
lazy.

Partial-Bug: 1224179
Change-Id: I80a85f3ddf2c41fe447df5682ad31ac4df8f8b59
(cherry picked from commit a0a359801e7248b24d15b3acef3b398d5a2fb65f)

commit_message:
Updated endpoints to support paths and ssl

- Add {public,admin,internal}_url parameters to override other
  {public,admin,internal}_ parameters.
- Also change some 'real_' prefix into '_real' suffix to respect the
coding guide.
- Fixed parsing the ssl/enable value in the provider.
- Update examples

Change-Id: I78d2695eb5cb1287538afe154668da9fe23e62a3
(cherry picked from commit 9cc9e347d5c65a387393995420c7a17a83fbda5a)

[{'created': '2014-01-07 13:57:34.000000000', 'message': 'Fix remove_warnings

Method lib/puppet/provider/keystone.rb/self.remove_providers does not
support multi line warnings and client results having more than one
column. This patch is fixing it (not sure how module can work with such
bug before anyway).

Change-Id: I19c3ce68ef786a2641d1e2808cb4db9979bdcfed
(cherry picked from commit e100e057bb2f6517fc6c5caad46a053864aa5328)
'}]
commit_message:
Fix remove_warnings

Method lib/puppet/provider/keystone.rb/self.remove_providers does not
support multi line warnings and client results having more than one
column. This patch is fixing it (not sure how module can work with such
bug before anyway).

Change-Id: I19c3ce68ef786a2641d1e2808cb4db9979bdcfed
(cherry picked from commit e100e057bb2f6517fc6c5caad46a053864aa5328)

commit_message:
Install oslo.sphinx from git

This is intended to fix the issues with oslo.config not being
found when running with devstack.  Having oslo.sphinx installed
via pip while oslo.config is installed from git means that
oslo.config cannot be found under some circumstances.

Change-Id: Iab974df43a5d5ca5356195ff55e4dc09b9c13093

Add API binding options

The [mysql] group technically only informs the command line client. We
should be using the [client] group which will inform libmysqlclient in
general. Note that there are still going to be programs that bypass this
file so it is not a perfect solution to the problem of different
binaries having different compiled in defaults for the socket.

Change-Id: Ic82a976b8591ef3a19e45f36ecc210104e670734
'}]
commit_message:
Use [client] instead of [mysql] in my.cnf

The [mysql] group technically only informs the command line client. We
should be using the [client] group which will inform libmysqlclient in
general. Note that there are still going to be programs that bypass this
file so it is not a perfect solution to the problem of different
binaries having different compiled in defaults for the socket.

Change-Id: Ic82a976b8591ef3a19e45f36ecc210104e670734

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-12 20:58:55.000000000', 'message': 'Translation Message improvements

The improvements to the current Message implementation include:

* Implementing a new method translate() to explicitely perform the
translation of a Message object, instead of relying on setting the
locale property.
* Remove inheriting from UserString and stop trying to make the Message
class act like a string, because that was causing problems with
consumers (e.g. the python log formatter) pretending the Message was a
string when it really was not.
* Remove the internal representation of the translated Message (i.e. the
data property) and simply return a unicode translation upon translate()
* Banning of the str() and unicode() methods, requiring users to always
use translate() to use this class.
* Enhancement to the corresponding TestTranslation class to enable fake
translations for multiple locales.


Partially implements: bp i18n-messages
Change-Id: I2dbddf422e79fd4474dede1e7c7ed229c89dc30c
'}, {'created': '2013-11-19 04:28:14.000000000', 'message': "Translation Message improvements

The improvements to the current Message implementation include:

* Implementing a new method translate() to explicitely perform the
translation of a Message object, instead of relying on setting the
'locale' property.
* All of the codebase assumes _() is a unicode object, so make the
Message unicode, that will always behave as unicode, except for the fact
that it has the extra ability to translate() on demand.
* Remove the internal representation of the translated Message (i.e. the
data property) and rely on parent implementations.
* Enhancement to the corresponding TestTranslation class to enable fake
translations for multiple locales.

With this patch the REST API translation in the other projects will work
with very minimal or no impact after re-enabling the 'lazy' _(). 

Partially implements: bp i18n-messages
Change-Id: I2dbddf422e79fd4474dede1e7c7ed229c89dc30c

commit_message:
Translation Message improvements

The improvements to the current Message implementation include:

* Implementing a new method translate() to explicitely perform the
translation of a Message object, instead of relying on setting the
'locale' property.
* All of the codebase assumes _() is a unicode object, so make the
Message unicode, that will always behave as unicode, except for the fact
that it has the extra ability to translate() on demand.
* Remove the internal representation of the translated Message (i.e. the
data property) and rely on parent implementations.
* Enhancement to the corresponding TestTranslation class to enable fake
translations for multiple locales.

With this patch the REST API translation in the other projects will work
with very minimal or no impact after re-enabling the 'lazy' _().

Partially implements: bp i18n-messages
Change-Id: I2dbddf422e79fd4474dede1e7c7ed229c89dc30c

commit_message:
Mark install-packages +x.

install-packages is an executable script, it should be +x.  The install
command that was installing it is setting permissions to 755, so we were
fine there.  However, I was trying to test the script outside of an
image build to test a change, and it's helpful to have it +x in the
repository for that context like all the other scripts under bin.

Change-Id: Ic300cc56d463640d119db4e310d375c66ed133ca

confision.

This minor change allows you to run rspec outside of strainer while
still having cookbook dependencies automatically handled by berkshelf
(which also means you can run individual chefspec tests).

Note that this change does marginally increase the time it takes to run
a strainer test.

If this change is accepted, then the remaining stackforge OpenStack
cookbooks will be updated also.

Change-Id: Ic50dcab83abd1937f9797444f36d477140abb183
"}]
commit_message:
Update spec_helper to include 'chefspec/berkshelf'

This minor change allows you to run rspec outside of strainer while
still having cookbook dependencies automatically handled by berkshelf
(which also means you can run individual chefspec tests).

Note that this change does marginally increase the time it takes to run
a strainer test.

If this change is accepted, then the remaining stackforge OpenStack
cookbooks will be updated also.

Change-Id: Ic50dcab83abd1937f9797444f36d477140abb183

commit_message:
Migrate network database

Migrate network database like other cookbooks do (openstack-identity,
openstack-nova,openstack-image etc.). The database migration will
make the OpenStack upgrade using the cookbooks easier.

The patch passes the template_file from common.rb to server.rb using
node['openstack']['network']['plugin_config_file'].

Change-Id: Ic98d2908876e45b870e32dfb37cfcd649962e2e6

commit_message:
Revert "Add pypi-openstack and pip-cache to common elements"

This reverts commit 54e7c72afae9f984c4ca8d4b57bba79a4eebbc25

pip-cache is not concurrent build safe, and the pypi mirror isn't available
over https, nor is it CDN'd.

Change-Id: I19e2a8781bb1d9053ebaf33828a7658295abf486

commit_message:
make AMQP support when develop_mode=false

When develop_mode=false, the password of mq user "guest"
in the databag user_passwords is required. But the current
code doesn't support. I made it work, and add the test cases.

Closes-Bug: #1257554
Change-Id: I0d01bd73eaec9cc90304e67484fec15fad061504

commit_message:
Using cliutils.arg() from oslo: common/cliutils.py

The decorator "arg" defined in "novaclient.utils" can be removed to
use the decorator from "common.clutils"

Related to blueprint common-client-library-2
Change-Id: Id84ad94b1a1d3820e25c30d2966fe159ef229bb8
Closes-Bug: 1266445

commit_message:
Fix install after nicira -> vmware folder rename

Both files are now located in the vmware folder, it seems
it is however not possible to include symlinks in distutils
tarballs, so this is not a complete fix, but makes pip
install succeed at least again.

Related-Bug: Bug #1266555

Change-Id: I09b71b4191019dd32b980fea4517e7f632eeab61

commit_message:
use openrc credentials to verify swift installation

Don't use the keystone admin token to authenticate, but a real user
instead (using the openrc.sh config file). This simplifies the swift
commands, and makes the verification more consistent with the
verification of other services.

Change-Id: I6a2512cb6cbb2942c9e8673f3f7d960f2f740e8e
backport: none

commit_message:
Add parameter --ignore-dir

This allows to ignore directories, e.g.
ignore in compute api the incubation and v1 dirs with:

openstack-doc-test --check-build --api-site \
  --ignore-dir=incubation --ignore-dir=openstack-compute-api-1.0

Change-Id: I6bad41543ed2269217a2ed36fcd947b83707daf2

commit_message:
Do not download RNG Schema, instead use local copies

Using local copies instead of remote ones speeds up the process
significantly since we do not need to download everytime more than
600 kb of data. The additional benefit is that testing now works
also while you're offline, no need to do any internet connection
for it.

The files change seldom, so it is fine to add them.

Tested with:
 time openstack-doc-test --api-site --check-syntax

Before this change:
real	0m4.020s
user	0m0.212s
sys	0m0.047s

After this change:
real	0m0.164s
user	0m0.142s
sys	0m0.022s

Change-Id: I541e75580ae734ccd5d48d699eb48225203646e8

commit_message:
Revert "Add pypi-openstack and pip-cache to common elements"

This reverts commit 54e7c72afae9f984c4ca8d4b57bba79a4eebbc25

pip-cache is not concurrent build safe, and the pypi mirror isn't available over https, nor is it CDN'd.

commit_message:
Rename nicira configuration elements to match new naming structure

- Every config item prefixed with nvp is prefixed with nsx
- deprecation qualifiers are added to preserve bw compatibility
- nicira/nvp.ini is renamed to vmware/nsx.ini
- symlink nicira/nvp.ini is created to point to vmware/nsx.ini
- UT added to verify that nvp.ini and old config items can still
  parsed correctly; bw-compat will be dropped in Juno

Partial-implements blueprint nicira-plugin-renaming

Change-Id: I676b868e61064cc5ff17e2246e83ba5c5e4a3449

commit_message:
Add pypi-openstack and pip-cache to common elements

They're both generally useful for image builds, and pypi-openstack
in particular works around the current issues with pip 1.5.

Change-Id: I679e57a0fff22cf3bf3a647845239855648132c2

commit_message:
Corrects broken format strings in check_i18n.py

In tools/check_i18n.py, the error messages printed out
had format strings that included 5 interpolations, but only
four variables were supplied. This patch simply corrects that
mismatch by including the name of the predicate or checker
that failed.

Closes-Bug: #1263813
Change-Id: I5cacee9ea000f56a9ef45f07367e85f20fa333c7

commit_message:
Python 3: use six.with_metaclass

Instead of using (Python 2):

    __metaclass__ = ...

or (Pyhon 3):

    class Foo(metaclass=...):

we use six.with_metaclass (Python 2 and 3):

    class Foo(six.with_metaclass(Meta, Base)):

Change-Id: Ie934cd14dfb81a018f838294b768e69dff16af5b

commit_message:
Python 3: replace 'basestring' by 'six.string_types'

'basestring' will only work in Python 2. Using 'six.string_types' instead makes
the code compatible with both Python 2 and 3.

Change-Id: I572506ce6d0cc7570dc264711d19619746949d49

commit_message:
Fix error in v3 credentials create/update

The v3 credentials passes data associated with the credential in
a "data" key, but the underlying API expects "blob", which is also
what is documented in the API spec.

Currently any attempt to create a credential with a type of 'ec2'
will fail with 'Invalid blob in credential' So s/data/blob to fix.

Change-Id: I0858e8c39653477eb554ee9d15fb4f2dde2b195c
Closes-Bug: #1259461

commit_message:
Migrate json to glance.openstack.common.jsonutils

Every call to json.loads/json.dumps have been changed to
jsonutils.loads/jsonutils.dumps respectively. Import json has been removed
also replaced by import glance.openstack.common.jsonutils

654d80b416dc5f413cb791aa838ec8688bf7da44 Create openstack.common.jsonutils

Change-Id: I8ef580e5eb91526dfaef37050ce1f5c6d88d56b5
Closes-bug: #1257922

commit_message:
Only move mysql data files if they exist

On first boot (on Fedora at least), these might not exist causing
the mv commands to fail.

Change-Id: I6bff5ab26d863c8991e11f11ee21c400211f70ec

commit_message:
Remove return stmt of add,save and remove method

Remove the add and save method's return statement in the
ImageMemberRepo class, as the same as ImageRepo class.  Also
modify authorization.py and policy.py and the related unittest.

Closes-Bug: #1254210

Closes-Bug: #1266483

commit_message:
Add .mailmap

The mailmap file is used when generating the AUTHORS file
and allows to merge entries by AUTHORS with several email
addresses into one canonical entry.

Added content to .mailmap to merge two addresses of
Ying Chun Guo

Change-Id: I5117ff27a796cf6cdda46f0c3adc3e01e9b88146

commit_message:
Add an option for ignoring h302 for some names

The H302 rule, allowing only importing of modules, is generally very
useful and helpful, but there are many places where it makes sense to
break it, due to convention and better readability. One such instance
is django.conf.settings, which is traditionally imported as:

    from django.conf import settings

but there are other such cases (gettext's _ comes to mind). Up until
now, we dealt with those cases by simply adding a #noqa comment. This
solution is, however, suboptimal, as it also silences all other
warnings, in particular ones about unused imports and alphabetic order
of imports.

This change adds a "h302_exceptions" option to the configuration of
Hacking, which allows us to list the names that are allowed to be
imported, even when they are not modules.

This will let us remove a lot of of "#noqa" from our code.

Change-Id: I7c22af198aa6f152bf13d1bd9ed68ab17ebea4dd

If we encounter an exception trying to gather async pendings 'async'
doesn't exist and the cronjob ends up erroring out and leaving behind a
stale lock file.

Change-Id: I70a6d3f00bd2c9ce742e6d16af93804280707040
"}]
commit_message:
Don't report async pendings on exception

If we encounter an exception trying to gather async pendings 'async'
doesn't exist and the cronjob ends up erroring out and leaving behind a
stale lock file.

Change-Id: I70a6d3f00bd2c9ce742e6d16af93804280707040

commit_message:
Add `deserialized_content` to the response

This is a helper method that aims to centralize response's content
deserialization and remove the burden of this process from the client.

Partially-Implements: python-marconiclient-v1
Change-Id: Ia98e9b9cdf5bdd88f9f2cdeda39b49d2192a60eb

@Angus, thanks for your suggestion.

But unfortunately it's not feasible. Since  calling $(get_data) is another process different from current shell script, it's impossible to quit the script in get_data function."}, {'account_id': 8641, 'date': '2013-12-13 03:24:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Another way is add a common function of die_if_not_set, which is probably merge devstack utilities: https://github.com/openstack-dev/devstack/blob/stable/havana/functions#L79-155'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2013-12-13 03:28:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Try this:
 cat call_fn.sh 
#!/bin/sh
get_data() {
  if [ -n "$1" ] ; then
    echo "oops exiting $1"
    exit 1
  fi
  echo $$
}
echo "script pid is $$"
echo "function pid=$(get_data)"
get_data "fail"
echo "don't get here"


./call_fn.sh 
script pid is 9956
function pid=9956
oops exiting fail

-----
what this proves is:
1: calling a function does not start a new process
2: you can generically fail/exit from a common function'}, {'account_id': 8641, 'date': '2013-12-13 04:09:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Angus, heat-keystone-setup call get_data function like below:

#!/bin/sh
get_data() {
  if [ -n "$1" ] ; then
    echo "oops exiting $1"
    exit 1
  fi
  echo $$
}
echo "script pid is $$"
echo "function pid=$(get_data)"
str=$(get_data "fail")
echo "don't get here"'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2013-12-17 20:47:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

I noticed tempest failed, I think you hit bug(s):

- https://bugs.launchpad.net/bugs/1254890

We don't automatically recheck or reverify, so please consider
doing that manually if someone hasn't already. For a code review
which is not yet approved, you can recheck by leaving a code
review comment with just the text:

    recheck bug 1254890

commit_message:
Do not abort on invalid XML

The deletions and build tests would abort if they tried to
parse a file that is not valid XML.

Now a warning message is printed and the check continues.

Change-Id: Idcb0330a5f94dc11c65540ee95ce80711c6853df

'}, {'account_id': 7156, 'date': '2013-12-09 16:37:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

The use case provided in the blueprint explains how this filter can be used to isolate windows images to a specific aggregate, probably for licensing purposes.

The actual implementation does not support double isolation: A windows image can still be booted on any hosts not part of the aggregate.

Therefore:
- an host belonging to an aggregate can only boot images matching its metadata (images with os=windows)
- an host not belonging to any aggregate can boot any images. (including images with os=windows)

Furthermore, an image having NO properties at all could still land on the host belonging to the aggregate.

Is this behaviour by design, a known limitation or is it an oversight?"}, {'account_id': 7730, 'date': '2013-12-10 14:39:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Hello Mathieu, thanks to take time on this commit.

The actual implementation try to be the more flexible has possible.
If you want to isolate windows image you HAVE to create an aggregate with a good property setted.
The filter first checks a match between KEY property then checks for a good value.

If I use your examples:
  "an host belonging to an aggregate can only boot images matching its metadata (images with os=windows)"
    it's false, this host can boot images without a property os setted.
  "an host not belonging to any aggregate can boot any images. (including images with os=windows)"
    it's false, if there is an aggregate with metadata os=windows the image will be booted on that host.


An example on how to use this filter:
  You have 3 hosts: A, B, C
  You have 3 kinds of images.
    You want windows images only on A
    You want rhel images on A and B
    You want ubuntu on any host A, B and C.

You can define an aggregate "windows" for the host A with a metadata "os=windows"
You can define an aggregate "rhel" for the host A, B with a metadata "os=rhel"
For ubuntu is is not necessary to create an aggregate.

(The exemple assumes you have correctly setted image property)

I hope it's understandable, tell me if you need more information or if you think i can update this filter to be more useful ;-)'}, {'account_id': 7156, 'date': '2013-12-10 17:32:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

An example on how to use this filter:
    You have 3 hosts: A, B, C
    You have 3 kinds of images.
      You want windows images only on A
      You want rhel images on A and B
      You want ubuntu on any host A, B and C.

The filter cannot address the USECASEs "You want windows images only on A" and "You want rhel images on A and B".

What you will have is:

  A will accept windows images, rhel images AND any other images.
  B will accept rhel images AND any other images.
  C will accept any other images. (including windows and rhel images)

Here is why.

AFAIK, a host filter can only tell if a particular host CAN accept or NOT an instance.

According to my understanding of the algorithm of the proposed filter, the following logic is used to determine if the host is valid or not for the instance:
  1) If an instance does not have any image properties, the host CAN accept it (irregardless of it being part of the aggregate or not).
  2) If an instance have ONE image property and is matching the corresponding host aggregate metadata, the host CAN accept it.
  3) If an instance have ONE image property and is NOT matching the corresponding host aggregate metadata, the host CANNOT accept it.
  4) If an instance have TWO image properties and only ONE is matching the corresponding host aggregate metadata, the host CANNOT accept it.
  5) If an instance have TWO image properties and NONE is matching the corresponding host aggregate metadata, the host CANNOT accept it.
  6) If an instance have TWO image properties and ALL are matching the corresponding host aggregate metadata, the host CAN accept it.
  7) If an instance have ANY image property and host is NOT part of ANY aggregate, the host CAN accept it.

Once host filtering is done, the result you get is a list of POSSIBLE hosts accepting your instance. The list is then sorted by weight and a random one is picked from the list, taking weight into account. [1] This means hosts found in 1), 2), 6) and 7) are part of the list.

My concerns are regarding 1) and 7). See USECASE below to understand WHY it is a concern.

The 1) could be easily addressed by introducing an additional host aggregate metadata rejecting any instance having NONE of the required image properties. This would add the ability to dedicate/reserve hosts for specific images.

The 7) means images meant to be isolated to the aggregate CAN still be accepted by hosts NOT part of the host aggregate. This is because those hosts are NOT rejected by the filter. This can hardly be addressed without knowing ALL available host aggregates and rejecting images if there is a known host aggregate that could accept them.

Therefore, according to the logic described above, the image WON'T be ISOLATED exclusively to the aggregate. In fact, a Windows image could still boot on a host not part of the host aggregate.

This filter is not about image ISOLATION but rather REJECTING any images not matching the host aggregate metadata. (and also accepting the ones without any properties defined)

This filter has limited usefulness with the USECASE mentioned in the blueprint [2]:

"The goal for this blueprint is [...] isolates an image from his properties to a host by the way of an aggregate."

Windows images are given as an example of the usefulness of the filter.

A real USECASE with Windows images is to isolate them on a particular host aggregate for licensing purposes. Hosts part of this aggregate require thousands of $ of licenses. You do NOT want this money wasted by filling the hosts with Linux images AND you do NOT want Windows images to boot elsewhere EVER for licensing and legal reasons.

This is why I strongly disagree with the logic and implementation of the filter. The USECASEs this filter tries to address are very limited or not well documented. The USECASE I have in mind (and that I thought we had in common) won't be able to use this filter because of its actual limitations which is a big letdown.

[1] https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/aggregate-host-isolation-based-image-properties
[2] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/nova/devref/filter_scheduler.html'}, {'account_id': 7730, 'date': '2013-12-10 18:49:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

@Mathieu this patch does what the blueprint said. To isolate an image on a specific host I invite you to take a look on isolated_hosts_filter.'}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2013-12-10 19:53:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
Aggregate: Hosts isolation based on image properties

Isolates hosts based on image properties and aggregate metadata
 - If a host doesn't belong to any aggregate it can create instances
   from all images.
 - if a host belongs to an aggregate and if this aggregate defines
   metadata that match with the image properties then the host
   is a candidate to boot the instance.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I3b9325e2e103f3bb6eed66789ac2c82941e94397
Implements: blueprint aggregate-host-isolation-based-image-properties

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-01-06 03:39:31.000000000', 'message': "Whitelist external netifaces requirement

* tox.ini(testenv.install_command): Use the --allow-external and
--allow-insecure options so that pip 1.5 and later will assent to
retrieve the netifaces package even though it's not hosted on PyPI.
The --allow-insecure option is aliased to a clearer
--allow-unverified wording in 1.5, but the old form is being used to
avoid breaking users of 1.4.x and will be valid at least through
1.6.x according to comments in the pip source.

commit_message:
Whitelist external netifaces requirement

* tox.ini(testenv.install_command): Use the --allow-external and
--allow-insecure options so that pip 1.5 and later will assent to
retrieve the netifaces package even though it's not hosted on PyPI.
The --allow-insecure option is aliased to a clearer
--allow-unverified wording in 1.5, but the old form is being used to
avoid breaking users of 1.4.x and will be valid at least through
1.6.x according to comments in the pip source.

Change-Id: I587b516f3f77c930475ca2eaae5ff73c5d2ab576
