Hi Armando,

Thanks for the review and sorry for the last response but i have some question for you if i may:


  * What is the the naming convention for the api_extensions list ? api_extensions="lbaas,metering,vpnaas" ? I am asking because the patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/58604 seem to be using CamelCase naming e.g. FlavorExtraData. 

I don't like the "all" default value because:

  * How can a tempest user know what are the available options to set to api_extensions ?  

  * As a tempest user if i want to disable one "extension" then i must know about all other extension available and set the api_extensions to that value (comma separated ) minus the extensions that i want to disable is this correct ? This seem like a very un-practical way of doing it ? 

Cheers,'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2013-12-18 10:30:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Hi Mouad,

The way I understand this, the api_extensions list would be the list of extension aliases separated by commas, so in the case of VPN And LB and Metering it is lbaas,vpnaas,metering as you referred before. If 'all' is specified, then by default all extensions are enabled.

I also appreciate your usability concerns in case you want just to disable a single extension, but I would bring them up to Matthew Treinish who is working on blueprint config-cleanup and may be able to give you an input as to why he decided to go forward with explicitly listing service extensions. Maybe a disabled_api_extensions (negative list) may be introduced to address some of your concerns, but I'd check with Matthew, to see if this is in its plans.

Cheers,
Armando"}, {'account_id': 7073, 'date': '2013-12-21 23:40:24.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-22 00:00:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Doesn't seem to work

'}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2013-12-23 17:36:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

So the checks are ok but I don't understand why the default is being changed from all to a list. Tempest is supposed to test all extensions. If some one adds a new neutron service then it will not be tested after this change. There is a discussion of the 'all' issue at this qa meeting http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/qa/2013/qa.2013-10-24-17.00.log.html starting at 17:18:14. There was a later suggestion to add another value for 'excluded' services but that got put off for now."}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2013-12-23 17:39:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: (1 inline comment)

I agree with David, see comment for details'}, {'account_id': 7073, 'date': '2013-12-23 19:58:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Thanks for the review.

I will put it back to "all" just a side note i have 3 remarks if i may, just something to take in consideration:

1- Like i said already in a previous change set if a user (don't think just devstack) want to use/configure tempest looking at the tempest.conf.sample will not be helpful for this value b/c "all" doesn't say much for him about what extensions are available so that he can choose which one to keep or no, and the ugly part is that he will have to grep the code to find out which one are supported by which service.

2- I don't like having both api_extenstions and exclude_extensions i doesn't really make sense for a point of view of a user that need to configure tempest, imagine something like this:

api_extensions = all
...
exclude_extentions = lbaas,metering

Now having both in a configuration file doesn't mean any sense at all, if you **have to** only change exclude_extentions, or else you will end up with inconsistency in your configuration, e.g.

 api_extensions = metering
 exclude_extentions = metering

WAT !? Who have precedence !? :)

3- having api_extensions list all extension put the burden on the developer and reviewers to make sure that any one that add a filter for a new extension should make sure that he update the default, which is IMHO better than other option b/c simply "user is king" :).

At least this how i think about this.

Cheers,'}, {'account_id': 7073, 'date': '2013-12-23 20:03:03.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2013-12-23 20:32:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: (1 inline comment)

Hi Mouad,

Thanks for your help.  As for your first point, the Neutron server exposes an API to tell you about extensions. You can use the CLI command neutron ext-list to learn about them.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-23 20:44:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: Doesn't seem to work

commit_message:
Do not close modal if escape is pressed on select

    The modal no longer fades out when pressing escape if a select is
open. After this, the select input is unfocused, so the second press
on escape will still close the modal.

Fixes bug #1265869

Change-Id: I49fa4431152fa3101bb6fafa6e07c8f908396ba8

commit_message:
Remove redundant code in nova_client.Client

'a and a or b' is equal to 'a or b', the redundant code can be
removed.

This patch also fixes the docstring of __init__, which actually
initializes a nova client object, not returns.

Change-Id: I0815928a2b597452048a1cc6c2170259a53ccaf9
Closes-Bug: #1264099

commit_message:
keystone trusts API test, move delete into tearDown handler

We want to prove the delete works for the various configurations of
trusts created in the tests, so move the delete into tearDown instead
of having a cleanup handler and explicit testing of delete in various
tests, and add a comment explaining why we do it like that.

Change-Id: I32f9aee5657ae54c1ca600f6ebe70bda81cd40e2

commit_message:
Add ovs_use_veth option

Add ovs_use_veth option in neutron::agents::dhcp and neutron::agents::l3.
The default value is false. In RHEL 6.5, it should set to true.

Change-Id: I508cdf847a4a57910a861c412270cdde13a6abc8
Closes-bug: 1264263

recheck bug1253896'}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2013-12-16 00:34:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: (3 inline comments)

A few questions inline.

One thing worth noting is that the synchronisation done in this way helps preventing preemption of the main loop, which is causing delays.
On the other hand however, it will cause processing of the various notifications to be held for a time which is potentially quite long (see bug 1253993). Therefore when the main iteration completes there could be a good deal of rpc calls to process; the drawback of this approach is that in some cases these are unicast notifications, but in other cases these are synchronous calls (eg: the l2 pop calls) which might then be blocked for a quite long time.

I'm not yet sure where to stand here, but I think at least the l2 pop code would probably benefit from synchronising the handlers."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-16 01:09:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
fix: duplicate opt error for sqlite when sharding

This patch adds support for using sqlite in a sharded context. It
ports a fix technique used for addressing the same problem in the
mongodb driver.

Change-Id: I6e79e95dd4eacff6cd3dfb5c22b03dc904fac5b2
Closes-Bug: #1264853

commit_message:
Fix test row execution

Logic that controlls test execution has been modified. Now all tests
have priority in exectution that controlls execution type. So now there
are excluseve tests which are started in child subprocesses and deffered
tests that are executed in same processes after exclusive finished.
Addition refactoring was added for testruns controller and TestRun
entity logic so that now when there are no exclusive test_sets in start
request body all of available are considered exlusive and are executed
simulateously. Unit tests were updated.

Logic of test run restart action was temporary disabled since it is not
valid now. Skipping for unit and functional tests were added.

Change-Id: If6d61515e9c3847366102d53534634c96f4d204e

commit_message:
Reuse common functional from cliutils

Module novaclient.utils has the same methods like in cliutils
from Oslo. In the process of unification of the clients code
we should reuse common functionality from Oslo.

Related to blueprint common-client-library-2

For changes like this it's sometimes nice to see the reference blueprint or bug that the change is supposed to address. Do you have a link?"}, {'account_id': 9415, 'date': '2013-12-17 04:11:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I am not aware of a bug report but would be happy to open one if you'd like.  I found this myself.

The vlan_network_ranges option applies to Open vSwitch and seems reasonably well documented as a "List of <physical_network>:<vlan_min>:<vlan_max> or <physical_network> tuples".  The validation in this module would likely not allow a simple <physical_network> -- but that could be considered another bug.

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/ConfigureOpenvswitch

Example ml2_conf.ini usage:
https://ask.openstack.org/en/question/7263/different-usecases-using-ml2/?answer=7326#post-id-7326'}, {'account_id': 7156, 'date': '2013-12-29 07:11:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

This bug fix can be referenced: 1264202

It's only a matter of amending your commit message and adding this reference at the end:

  Closes-bug: #1264202"}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2013-12-29 11:20:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

-1 because a patch is already under review:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/55578
which affect this class.

The patch is now abandoned, I already emailed with the owner and I think it's stalled during holiday time."}, {'account_id': 7822, 'date': '2013-12-29 19:35:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: No score

Which patch was abandoned?'}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2013-12-29 20:40:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Chris: this one: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/55578

I think it's because of holidays, I'll care of this one which is quite important."}, {'account_id': 7822, 'date': '2013-12-30 19:49:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm being dense. Which patch do we want to keep? Which one do we want to drop? Sorry :-P"}, {'account_id': 9415, 'date': '2013-12-30 22:06:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

My change (62447 / I8e61408e) is targeted directly at my problem: VLAN networking is broken today (because the name of the network must be specified in network_vlan_ranges, and the validate function prohibits this).  This patch alters the validation to REQUIRE the network name.

The other patch (55578 / Ic51ed794) is a large patch (adding VXLAN support) that also happens to alter the validation function to PERMIT specifying a network name.  This is sufficient to permit VLAN networking to work, but no tests are added/created to address the issue in this (62447) patch and the default network_vlan_ranges value (10:50) is not changed.  I'm not sure if it would ever be valid to specify network_vlan_ranges without a network name."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2014-01-07 06:03:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2014-01-07 06:03:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}]

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-10 07:40:54.000000000', 'message': 'Change from eager load to lazy load

Eager load causes data inconsistency when the dhcp port
is deleted asynchronously, which recycles the IP address. This would
eventually merge the IP to the records in IPAvailabilityRange
table. Using eager load, the data for the IPAvailabilityRange table
is not consistent, which causes the subnet-delete to fail.

Fixes bug 1257815

Change-Id: If5330123fa7e3c40a9b8106c4d876dd4e6249049
'}, {'created': '2013-12-10 08:28:48.000000000', 'message': 'Change from eager load to lazy load

commit_message:
Change from eager load to lazy load

Eager load causes data inconsistency when the dhcp port
is deleted asynchronously, which recycles the IP address. This would
eventually merge the IP to the records in IPAvailabilityRange
table. Using eager load, the data for the IPAvailabilityRange table
is not consistent, which causes the subnet-delete to fail.

Fixes bug 1257815

Change-Id: If5330123fa7e3c40a9b8106c4d876dd4e6249049

commit_message:
Update V2 API to return detailed volume information on create

Current implementation returns only summary information, so
cinderclient requires additional GET call to get details.
Updated the api to return the details by default so the GET in
cinderclient can be removed.

Closes-Bug: #1265893

Change-Id: I56d4d79c4a942d8bf53318e46737674dc0bf9b56

commit_message:
Use oslo db.migration script

Turn Heat's migration script into a simple wrapper around olso's.
The api is a bit different so for now keep ours inplace.
All that our script does is find the path to the migration_repo
and call the oslo code. No point having two implementations in the
same codebase.

Change-Id: I0aa3e10890f924d77268f4118dae53b446e193eb

commit_message:
Configure undercloud to use ext4 ephemeral FS

Ext4 is significantly more efficient when being created, and we do not
need to support older OS's or platforms that do not support ext4.

This will be ineffective until the change to the nova element lands,
but it is harmless to land this first. That change is referenced by this
Gerrit change ID in tripleo-image-elements:

Ic754f3b342b632a6919d4ad1b808627ec9fa4308

Closes-Bug: #1266262
Change-Id: Icca5fd94ca230141818ee9adb416f6f062869c6b

commit_message:
Allow setting nova default_ephemeral_format

We need to allow setting default_ephemeral_format so that the overcloud
can retain the default value but the undercloud can use ext4 to reduce
deploy times when writing ephemeral filesystems.

Change-Id: Ic754f3b342b632a6919d4ad1b808627ec9fa4308
Partial-Bug: #1266262

commit_message:
Pin virtualenv to 1.10.1 to work around pip bug

If 1.11 is used with --system-site-packages pip won't be installed in
the virtualenv, leading to an activated virtualenv not using pip and
thus not installing anything into the virtualenv.

Change-Id: Ic9907438b17ca9a32fbeccc4ca806b8b43f41cd1
Partial-Bug: #1266513

A user reported a missing section in the Havana admin guide for
creating and attaching floating IP addresses. As many users still
use nova-network I thought this should be put back in. I've added
a note to point towards the basic neutron equivalent. For the Icehouse
manual we should add more detail to support the floating IP concepts in

Closes-Bug: #1263203

commit_message:
Added section for Floating IP creation in Havana admin guide

A user reported a missing section in the Havana admin guide for
creating and attaching floating IP addresses. As many users still
use nova-network I thought this should be put back in. I've added
a note to point towards the basic neutron equivalent. For the Icehouse
manual we should add more detail to support the floating IP concepts in
Neutron.

Change-Id: Iaa4387461a6f4775acf1f86dfde7b8afe226495f
Closes-Bug: #1263203

commit_message:
Refactor Instance#_check_active

Currently, Instance#_check_active both checks whether the server is
active and attaches the volume. This commit separates that logic.

blueprint stack-check
Change-Id: I7fe805efc089535667e8d3840d79ade07430040c

instead of inheriting from the QueueTestBase.

commit_message:
Eliminate extra newlines in generated workflow.xml

When the base workflow in service/edp/resources/workflow.xml is read
newlines are preserved in the text elements.  Additional elements are
added without newlines and newlines are inserted when the text is
generated.  This causes extra newlines after the original elements.

This change strips whitespace from the beginning and end of each
line in the base workflow file when it is first read, which eliminates
the extra newlines in the text elements.

Closes-Bug: #1265916

Change-Id: Ibf75cdf54c3218df9d0085005624b3ee8d4c0ea5

commit_message:
Add a Client 'instantiator'

This function mocks a class constructor but returns a client instance
for the specified version. This reduces the number of imports needed to
use the API and makes it easier to migrate from one version to the
other.

Change-Id: I20bb9adef4fa4f6bb87c53020454c791d765c389
Partially-Implements: python-marconiclient-v1

commit_message:
Move request_and_transport to the Client

This patch moves the `_get_transport` and `request_and_transport` method
to the client. Both method are useful for other resources like Message,
for example.

This patch also moves the is_functional logic to the BaseTest class and
splits unittests from functional tests.

Partially-Implements: python-marconiclient-v1
Change-Id: Iaf56c234291b355c98817feee5644a5dd07c0b7f

[{'created': '2014-01-06 18:25:41.000000000', 'message': 'Generic means for persisting system metadata.

Middleware or core features may need to store metadata
against accounts or containers. This patch adds a
generic mechanism for system metadata to be persisted
in backend databases, without polluting the user
metadata namespace, by using the reserved header
namespace x-<server_type>-sysmeta-*.

Modifications are firstly that backend servers persist
system metadata headers alongside user metadata and
other system state.

For accounts and containers, system metadata in PUT
and POST requests is treated in a similar way to user
metadata. System metadata is not yet supported for
object requests.

Secondly, changes in the proxy controllers ensure that
headers in the system metadata namespace will pass through
in requests to backend servers. A convenience function
(swift.common.request_helpers.add_sys_meta) is provided
for middleware to add system metadata to a request, and
as a heads-up to developers that the reserved namespace
exists.

Thirdly, system metadata returned from backend servers
in GET or HEAD responses is added to the cached info
dict, which middleware can access.

Finally, a gatekeeper middleware module is provided
which filters all system metadata headers from requests
and responses by removing headers with names starting
x-account-sysmeta-, x-container-sysmeta-. The gatekeeper
also removes headers starting x-object-sysmeta- in
anticipation of future support for system metadata being
set for objects. This prevents clients from writing or
reading system metadata.

The required_filters list in swift/proxy/server.py is
modified to include the gatekeeper middleware so that
the gatekeeper will be automatically inserted close to
the start of the pipeline if it has not been configured.

blueprint cluster-federation

Change-Id: I80b8b14243cc59505f8c584920f8f527646b5f45

commit_message:
Generic means for persisting system metadata.

Middleware or core features may need to store metadata
against accounts or containers. This patch adds a
generic mechanism for system metadata to be persisted
in backend databases, without polluting the user
metadata namespace, by using the reserved header
namespace x-<server_type>-sysmeta-*.

Modifications are firstly that backend servers persist
system metadata headers alongside user metadata and
other system state.

For accounts and containers, system metadata in PUT
and POST requests is treated in a similar way to user
metadata. System metadata is not yet supported for
object requests.

Secondly, changes in the proxy controllers ensure that
headers in the system metadata namespace will pass through
in requests to backend servers. A convenience function
(swift.common.request_helpers.add_sys_meta) is provided
for middleware to add system metadata to a request, and
as a heads-up to developers that the reserved namespace
exists.

Thirdly, system metadata returned from backend servers
in GET or HEAD responses is added to the cached info
dict, which middleware can access.

Finally, a gatekeeper middleware module is provided
which filters all system metadata headers from requests
and responses by removing headers with names starting
x-account-sysmeta-, x-container-sysmeta-. The gatekeeper
also removes headers starting x-object-sysmeta- in
anticipation of future support for system metadata being
set for objects. This prevents clients from writing or
reading system metadata.

The required_filters list in swift/proxy/server.py is
modified to include the gatekeeper middleware so that
the gatekeeper will be automatically inserted close to
the start of the pipeline if it has not been configured.

blueprint cluster-federation

Change-Id: I80b8b14243cc59505f8c584920f8f527646b5f45

removed wsgi manipulation, adopted minor changes and corrections from cf-sysmeta-review9

Change-Id: Ibfb4579cd4d4600acaaa0ba94f196ca1798b0d2f

commit_message:
Adjust import order according to PEP8 imports rule

This patch just adjust import order to follow PEP8 imports rule.
See http://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/#imports

Imports should be grouped in the following order:
1) Standard library imports
2) Related third party imports
3) Local application/library specific imports

Change-Id: I7f85e7701cb5f7b81a5cc4b8666c1e8302b6ac52

commit_message:
Reduce log level on lvremove retry message

Reduce the log level from ERROR to WARNING when we detect an
initial failure calling lvremove in order to prevent devstack
gate jobs from reporting failure via log analysis

Change-Id: I6a730348a75b707beb9d693f5dc97edbb54ccfe5
Closes-Bug: #1259771

Add check_uptodate to tools/config

Add a script which can be used to validate a project's
sample config and ensure that it remains up to date on every commit.

commit_message:
driver-list command to show the list of conductors

The commit https://review.openstack.org/#/c/60216/ returns the name of the
drivers and also a list of active conductors that supports each driver,
this patch makes the necessary changes to expose that information on
the driver-list command.

Change-Id: I9183b40422f6dc3193570703d25d47b6e8edde06

[{'created': '2013-12-19 01:03:23.000000000', 'message': 'Improve error handling in PXE _continue_deploy

Related to bug 1184470, there was a concern that the PXE driver
may not be adequately handling errors and informing users when failures
occur mid-deploy.

This patch refactors the _continue_deploy() method to handle both errors
POSTed from the ramdisk and errors that originate within deploy_utils.

It also fixes an inconsistency in the final provisioning_state:
ConductorManager.do_node_deploy() will set provisioning_state = ACTIVE,
however the PXE driver was leaving nodes with state = DEPLOYDONE.

Change-Id: I29cbff87cbaf85d95687ae094720f8b99f33b65f
Related-to: 1184470

commit_message:
Improve error handling in PXE _continue_deploy

Related to bug 1184470, there was a concern that the PXE driver
may not be adequately handling errors and informing users when failures
occur mid-deploy.

This patch refactors the _continue_deploy() method to handle both errors
POSTed from the ramdisk and errors that originate within deploy_utils.

It also fixes an inconsistency in the final provisioning_state:
ConductorManager.do_node_deploy() will set provisioning_state = ACTIVE,
however the PXE driver was leaving nodes with state = DEPLOYDONE.

Change-Id: I29cbff87cbaf85d95687ae094720f8b99f33b65f
Related-bug: 1184470

ironic client should display chassis_uuid value

Our Node API return chassis_uuid value correctly, but ironic client
display chassis_id with empty value, so change to chassis_uuid.

Closes-Bug: #1265785

[{'created': '2014-01-05 02:04:12.000000000', 'message': 'Clarified installation of Networking on dedicated controller node

I clarified various portions of the section for installing Networking
on a dedicated controller node. This patch covers all of the issues
provided in the associated bug. In light of freezing Havana and moving
focus to Icehouse with more significant changes, this patch also
contains several more ambitious clarifications:

1) Reorder various steps to improve flow and consistency with
configuration of other services. For example, other services generally
configure access to the MySQL database fairly early in the section.

2) Combine similar steps. For example, configuring Networking to use
Keystone involves editing neutron.conf and api-paste.ini. Rather than
using two separate steps which may change location and ordering with
future patches, I combined them into one step with substeps for each
file.

3) For the steps affected by this bug, I changed project names to
service names as provided in the conventions section of the
documentation guide.

Change-Id: I04eee95711e3a25e06641602f37b801a659b9e35
Closes-Bug: #1264170
'}]
commit_message:
Clarified installation of Networking on dedicated controller node

I clarified various portions of the section for installing Networking
on a dedicated controller node. This patch covers all of the issues
provided in the associated bug. In light of freezing Havana and moving
focus to Icehouse with more significant changes, this patch also
contains several more ambitious clarifications:

1) Reorder various steps to improve flow and consistency with
configuration of other services. For example, other services generally
configure access to the MySQL database fairly early in the section.

2) Combine similar steps. For example, configuring Networking to use
Keystone involves editing neutron.conf and api-paste.ini. Rather than
using two separate steps which may change location and ordering with
future patches, I combined them into one step with substeps for each
file.

3) For the steps affected by this bug, I changed project names to
service names as provided in the conventions section of the
documentation guide.

Change-Id: I04eee95711e3a25e06641602f37b801a659b9e35
Closes-Bug: #1264170

commit_message:
Handle more nicely when role root is already here

When using postgresql we were handling the fallback if the role root was
already here but this was still printing an error message, try to make
it a bit smarter.

Closes-Bug: #1265477
Change-Id: Ib3768dd182ab968e81038f900550f641b9a2af5c

commit_message:
Make admin-mode a CLI parameter

Admin mode enables/disables the admin endpoints. It's currently
implemented as a configuration option. It'd be useful to expose it as a
CLI parameter as well in order to ease the 'creation' of admin nodes
either from init scripts or manually without modifying the 'global'
config.

Closes-bug: #1244228
Change-Id: I3f138d8674ced180fc747c425ab85b0ed0e9e42a

commit_message:
Allowing snapshoting attached volume

The cinder api allows calling snapshot on attached volumes,
we should enable it on horizon.

Change-Id: I33d7bbca0bf993ace7c243867aa5f57438a57a5d
Fixes: bug #1202929

commit_message:
Make sure a loop device exists before kpartx is called

If "kpartx -av" is called and there is no unused /dev/loop* device,
then kpartx fails. Calling "losetup -f" finds first unused device
and creates it if it doesn't exist.

Fixes bug #1195264

Change-Id: I5d59b519fd8e2a7380b71a788f9d3f2331b6567f

commit_message:
Glanceclient should switch to using bufferedhttp

Glanceclient should switch to using bufferedhttp like in swift which
makes up for missing features in traditional httplib, for eg)
buffering http headers, support for 'Expect: 100-continue' etc.
This patch pulls in the bufferedhttp from swift.

Related to bp use-buffered-http-inglance-client
Change-Id: I65f0b0f62f5d89bc8dd24b1260531e1f1d3555c8

Remove unused dict BYTE_MULTIPLIERS

Dict BYTE_MULTIPLIERS in ironic/common/utils.py isn't used
anywhere, and ironic/openstack/common/strutils.py includes
this dict, So we can use the one in oslo if we need. It's
safe to remove it now.

commit_message:
always use sitepackages

we really don't need to be compiling lxml at 3.5 when 2.3 is good
enough. So specify that we can always use sitepackages, as well
as don't pip -U, so we use requirements as intended.

Change-Id: If9f337d6bb688d46ab68dc1276e0f499a7dec8fd

commit_message:
Make param names more consistent in API

Param names for resource ids were inconsistent in the API. This patch
converts them to *_uuid form.

Closes-Bug: #1259619
Change-Id: Icb6cb1f9ebab7c9d516ec297eeee6f2db8b52eb2

[{'created': '2014-01-05 16:08:00.000000000', 'message': 'Make running of unit tests more robust

Unit tests would fail if run from a symlinked directory.
To fix this, this patch adds the -P switch to the pwd command,
to make sure all files are referred to by their actual paths
and not symlinks.

Change-Id: Ib7087c11f9dc2c44be3aca8cf94db227a2db72f3
Closes-Bug: #1266220
'}]
commit_message:
Make running of unit tests more robust

Unit tests would fail if run from a symlinked directory.
To fix this, this patch adds the -P switch to the pwd command,
to make sure all files are referred to by their actual paths
and not symlinks.

Change-Id: Ib7087c11f9dc2c44be3aca8cf94db227a2db72f3
Closes-Bug: #1266220

commit_message:
Fix group ticket URI in KDS API

According to my understanding of the KDS API doc, the ticket retrieval
mechanism for a group destination is the same as for a single
destination. In which case, the URI used by the source to retrieve the
ticket should be the same in both case: /v1/tickets. In the current
document, the URI to be used to get a group ticket seems bogus
(/v1/groups). This patch fixes the inconsistency.

Change-Id: Ibdea2d73e8d20f821b371ed42f179dcbac2b2419
